{"title_page": "Blaine Anderson", "text_new": "{{For|the federal judge|J. Blaine Anderson}}\n{{short description|Fictional character from the Fox series Glee}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name = Blaine Anderson\n| image = Blaine Glee Tour Silly.jpg\n| caption = [[Darren Criss]] as Blaine Anderson during [[Glee Live! In Concert!]]\n| series = [[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]\n| first = \"[[Never Been Kissed (Glee)|Never Been Kissed]]\"\n| last = \"[[Dreams Come True (Glee)|Dreams Come True]]\"\n| portrayer = [[Darren Criss]]\n| occupation = student, singer, glee club director, actor\n| creator = [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]]<br/>[[Brad Falchuk]]<br/>[[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]]\n| spouse = [[Kurt Hummel]] (husband)\n| family = Pam Anderson (mother)<br />Cooper Anderson (brother)<br>Unnamed Daughter\n| significant other = [ Kurt Hummel ]\n}}\n'''Blaine Devon Anderson'''<ref name=\"Feud\">{{cite episode |title=Feud|episodelink=Feud (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=March 14, 2013 |season=4 |number=16}}</ref> is a fictional character from the American musical comedy-drama television series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]''. Played by [[Darren Criss]], Blaine was introduced in the [[Never Been Kissed (Glee)|sixth episode]] of the [[Glee (season 2)|second season]] as the [[openly gay]] lead singer of the Dalton Academy Warblers, a rival show choir to New Directions, the show's primary musical group. Blaine initially served as a mentor for New Directions member [[Kurt Hummel]] ([[Chris Colfer]]). Chemistry between the two, combined with fan support for the couple, led series co-creator [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] to pair them romantically. Their relationship has been well received by critics, and they have been named \"one of the most beloved TV couples of the millennium\" by Jarett Wieselman of the ''[[New York Post]]''.<ref name=\"NYP\"/> At the beginning of the third season, Blaine transfers to McKinley High and joins New Directions; concurrently, Criss was promoted from recurring guest star to the show's main cast.\n\nCriss auditioned for ''Glee'' several times before being cast as Blaine, including for the lead role of [[Finn Hudson]]. He believed he would be ill-suited to that character, but identifies with Blaine, having been raised among the \"gay community\".<ref name=\"kurt's new squeeze\"/> He plays Blaine as charismatic and confident, and finds his youthful self-acceptance a fitting counterpoint to common media portrayals of gay characters.\n\nAs the Warblers' lead vocalist and subsequent New Directions member, Blaine has performed a number of songs on the television series. His first, a [[cover version]] of \"[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry song)|Teenage Dream]]\" by [[Katy Perry]], became the fastest-selling ''Glee'' single, reached number eight on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and was certified gold in the U.S.<ref name=\"bill20101127\"/><ref name=\"riaa\"/> Tracks by the Warblers have sold over 1.3&nbsp;million copies. The songs became popular enough to warrant a Warbler soundtrack album, ''[[Glee: The Music Presents the Warblers]]''. Blaine has received mostly positive reviews from critics; Criss has been awarded a Rising Star accolade from the Gay and Lesbian Entertainment Critics Association for his portrayal. While the Blaine\u2013Kurt (\"Klaine\") relationship has been met with acclaim, an episode storyline in which Blaine questioned his sexuality attracted negative reviews for undermining his previous characterization as a confident gay teenager.\n\n==Storylines==\n===Season 2===\nBlaine Anderson is introduced in the episode \"[[Never Been Kissed (Glee)|Never Been Kissed]]\" as the lead soloist of the Dalton Academy Warblers [[a cappella]] musical group, and honestly changed Glee for the better. He meets [[Kurt Hummel]] ([[Chris Colfer]]), a member of the rival [[glee club]] New Directions. When Kurt asks if Blaine is gay, Blaine matter-of-factly says he is; Kurt tells Blaine that he is being bullied at school for being gay, and Blaine reveals that he too was harassed at his old school, so he transferred to Dalton Academy, which enforces a no-bullying policy. Blaine befriends Kurt, and helps him stand up to his tormentor, [[Dave Karofsky]] ([[Max Adler (actor)|Max Adler]]).<ref name=\"NY\">{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/11/glee_recap_teenage_dream.html|title=Glee Recap: Teenage Dream|date=November 10, 2010|first=Rebecca|last=Milzoff|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|publisher=New York Media Holdings|accessdate=November 10, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN-NeverBeenKissed\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/113/1133366p1.html|title=Glee: \"Never Been Kissed\" Review|date=November 10, 2010|first=Robert|last=Canning|publisher=IGN|accessdate=November 10, 2010}}</ref> When the threats and violence against Kurt reach a dangerous level, he transfers to Dalton Academy.<ref>{{cite web|first=Robert|last=Canning|url=http://au.tv.ign.com/articles/113/1136637p1.html|accessdate=2011-01-02|title=Glee: \"Furt\" Review&nbsp;\u2014 TV Review at IGN|work=[[IGN]]|date=November 24, 2010}}</ref> He falls in love with Blaine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2010/12/glee-review-a-very-glee-christmas/|title=Glee Review: You're a Sweet One, Sue the Grinch|work=TV Fanatic|first=Matt|last=Richenthal|date=December 8, 2010|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> who is initially oblivious to Kurt's feelings even as their friendship grows. Blaine enlists Kurt's help to serenade his crush Jeremiah (Alexander Nifong), the assistant manager at a local Gap store. Jeremiah is subsequently fired and rebuffs Blaine. Kurt confesses his feelings, and Blaine tells Kurt that he cares for him, but is terrible at romance and does not want to risk damaging their friendship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2011/02/glee-review-silly-love-songs/|title=Glee Review: Lots of Luck, Santana|last=Richenthal|first=Matt|date=February 8, 2011|work=TV Fanatic|accessdate=February 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nKurt and Blaine attend a party hosted by New Directions co-captain [[Rachel Berry]] ([[Lea Michele]]). The attendees play [[spin the bottle]], which results in Rachel and Blaine kissing. In the aftermath, Blaine wonders whether he might be bisexual, and goes on a date with Rachel. When she kisses him again while they are both sober, he concludes that he is indeed gay, which relieves Kurt.<ref name=\"sc\">{{cite web|url=http://screencrave.com/2011-02-23/glee-season-2-episode-14-blame-it-on-the-alcohol-tv-review/|title=Glee: Season 2 Episode 14: Blame It On the Alcohol -TV Review|last=Butler|first=Candace|date=February 22, 2011|work=ScreenCrave|accessdate=February 23, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022431/http://screencrave.com/2011-02-23/glee-season-2-episode-14-blame-it-on-the-alcohol-tv-review/|archivedate=July 16, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter learning of Kurt\u2019s ignorance of sexual matters, Blaine visits Kurt's father, [[Burt Hummel|Burt]] ([[Mike O'Malley]]), and prompts him to give Kurt \"[[the birds and the bees|the talk]]\" about sex.<ref name=\"Sexy\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/03/09/glee-season-2-episode-15-sexy-tv-recap/?mod=google_news_blog|title={{-'}}Glee' Season 2, Episode 15 'Sexy': TV Recap|last=Flandez|first=Raymund|date=March 9, 2011|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|accessdate=March 9, 2011}}</ref> As the Warblers prepare to perform at the Regional show choir competition, Kurt admits that he is jealous of how many solos Blaine gets. At a subsequent group meeting, Kurt arrives late and announces that the group's mascot canary is dead; he sings \"[[Blackbird (Beatles song)|Blackbird]]\" in honor of the bird. While Kurt is singing, Blaine has a revelation, and later tells Kurt that he reciprocates his feelings and kisses him. At Regionals, the two sing a duet of \"Candles\" by [[Hey Monday]]. The Warblers lose to New Directions, but while Kurt is very disappointed, Blaine tells him that even though they lost, in reality, they won each other which makes losing Regionals worth it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2011/03/16/2011-03-16_glee_season_2_episode_16_kurt_and_blaine_kiss_in_midst_of_original_song_tracks.html|title={{-'}}Glee' Season 2, Episode 16 'Original Song: TV Recap|last=Flandez|first=Raymund|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|accessdate=March 17, 2011}}</ref> After Kurt transfers back to McKinley, he invites Blaine to be his date at his junior prom in \"[[Prom Queen (Glee)|Prom Queen]]\"; both are shocked when Kurt wins Prom Queen due to having received an overwhelming number of unwanted write-in votes in the secret balloting. Karofsky, the Prom King, leaves to avoid dancing with a guy in the traditional dance between King and Queen, and Kurt dances with Blaine instead.<ref name=\"Prom Queen\">{{cite episode |title=Prom Queen |episodelink=Prom Queen (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Ian Brennan (writer), Eric Stoltz (director)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=May 10, 2011 |season=2 |number=20}}</ref> After Kurt returns from Nationals in New York, he and Blaine admit their love for one another.<ref name=\"New York\">{{cite episode |title=New York |episodelink=New York (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Brad Falchuk (director, writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=May 24, 2011 |season=2 |number=22}}</ref>\n\n===Season 3===\nIn the first episode of the [[Glee (season 3)|third season]], \"[[The Purple Piano Project]]\", Blaine transfers to McKinley High at the beginning of his junior year to be closer to Kurt, who is a senior, and joins New Directions.<ref name=\"Purple\">{{cite episode |title=The Purple Piano Project|episodelink=The Purple Piano Project|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Eric Stoltz]] (director), [[Brad Falchuk]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=September 20, 2011 |season=3 |number=1}}</ref> He later auditions for the role of Bernardo in the school musical ''[[West Side Story]]'', so as not to compete against Kurt who wants to play the male lead, Tony, but is cast as Tony himself.<ref name=\"Unicorn\">{{cite episode |title=I Am Unicorn|episodelink=I Am Unicorn|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Brad Falchuk]] (director), [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=September 27, 2011 |season=3 |number=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Asian F\">{{cite episode |title=Asian F|episodelink=Asian F|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Alfonso Gomez-Rejon]] (director), [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=October 4, 2011 |season=3 |number=3}}</ref> In the episode \"[[The First Time (Glee)|The First Time]]\", Blaine is pursued by [[Sebastian Smythe]] ([[Grant Gustin]]), a new Dalton Academy Warbler. Kurt and Blaine meet up with Sebastian at a gay bar, Blaine gets drunk, and afterward tries to get Kurt to have sex with him in the car. Kurt refuses, they have a fight, and Blaine decides to walk home. After the ''West Side Story'' opening night, they apologize to each other, and decide to go to Blaine's house. They are later shown in bed together, apparently having just had sex for the first time.<ref name=\"First Time\">{{cite episode |title=The First Time|episodelink=The First Time (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=November 8, 2011 |season=3 |number=5}}</ref> When New Directions and the Warblers informally compete in \"[[Michael (Glee)|Michael]]\" to determine which club can perform [[Michael Jackson]]'s music at the upcoming show choir Regionals, Sebastian throws a slushie containing rock salt at Kurt, but Blaine interposes himself and is hit in the eye; his cornea is badly scratched and requires surgery.<ref name=\"Michael\">{{cite episode |title=Michael|episodelink=Michael (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Alfonso Gomez-Rejon]] (director), [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=January 31, 2012 |season=3 |number=11}}</ref> His eye heals, and he is back in time for New Directions to defeat the Warblers at Regionals.<ref name=\"On My Way\">{{cite episode |title=On My Way|episodelink=On My Way (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=February 21, 2012 |season=3 |number=14}}</ref> Blaine's older brother Cooper ([[Matt Bomer]]), a successful actor in commercials, visits Ohio, and the two achieve a rapprochement.<ref name=\"Big Brother\">{{cite episode |title=Big Brother|episodelink=Big Brother (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Eric Stoltz]] (director), [[Michael Hitchcock]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=April 10, 2012 |season=3 |number=15}}</ref> Blaine's relationship with Kurt is later strained when Kurt text-flirts with a boy he met while preparing for his NYADA audition, and by Kurt's eagerness to leave for New York after graduation, which would separate the two at least until Blaine graduated the following year.<ref name=\"Dance with Somebody\">{{cite episode |title=Dance with Somebody|episodelink=Dance with Somebody (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Paris Barclay]] (director), Ross Maxwell (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=April 24, 2012 |season=3 |number=17}}</ref> The two patch things up, the glee club wins at Nationals, and the pair is still a couple at the end of the school year, though Blaine is still uneasy about the prolonged physical separation facing them.<ref name=\"Goodbye\">{{cite episode |title=Goodbye|episodelink=Goodbye (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Brad Falchuk]] (director, writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=May 22, 2012 |season=3 |number=22}}</ref>\n\n===Season 4===\nIn the first episode of the [[Glee (season 4)|fourth season]], \"[[The New Rachel]]\", Blaine becomes the lead singer of New Directions and successfully prompts Kurt to follow his New York City dreams.<ref name=\"New Rachel\">{{cite episode |title=The New Rachel|episodelink=The New Rachel|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Brad Falchuk]] (director), [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=September 13, 2012 |season=4 |number=1}}</ref> In addition, Blaine successfully runs for senior class president with [[Sam Evans|Sam]] ([[Chord Overstreet]]), and the two subsequently develop a friendship.<ref name=\"Makeover\">{{cite episode |title=Makeover |episodelink=Makeover (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Eric Stoltz]] (director), [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]] (writer) |network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=September 27, 2012 |season=4 |number=3}}</ref> Kurt inadvertently pulls away from Blaine due to his Vogue.com internship; distraught and feeling isolated from his friends, Blaine cheats on Kurt.<ref name=\"Makeover\"/><ref name=\"Break Up\">{{cite episode |title=The Break Up|episodelink=The Break Up (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Alfonso Gomez-Rejon]] (director), [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=October 4, 2012 |season=4 |number=4}}</ref> After confessing to Kurt of his infidelity, Kurt severs all ties.<ref name=\"Break Up\"/> New Directions' Nationals trophy is stolen by Hunter Clarington ([[Nolan Gerard Funk]]), the new captain of the Dalton Academy Warblers.<ref name=\"Dynamic\">{{cite episode |title=Dynamic Duets |episodelink=Dynamic Duets|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]] (writer and director) |network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=November 22, 2012 |season=4 |number=7}}</ref> When Blaine goes to Dalton Academy to retrieve it, Hunter and Sebastian attempt to seduce Blaine into returning to the Warblers. Blaine becomes conflicted, believing that he does not belong in New Directions.<ref name=\"Dynamic\"/> Sam ultimately convinces him that, despite having done a bad thing to Kurt, Blaine is still a good person and an important member of New Directions.<ref name=\"Dynamic\"/>\n\nKurt begins to mend their relationship in \"[[Thanksgiving (Glee)|Thanksgiving]]\", just before New Directions loses at Sectionals to the Warblers, and they spend Christmas together in New York City.<ref name=\"Thanksgiving\">{{cite episode |title=Thanksgiving|episodelink=Thanksgiving (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), [[Russel Friend]] & [[Garrett Lerner]] (writers)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=November 29, 2012 |season=4 |number=8}}</ref><ref name=\"Actually\">{{cite episode |title=Glee, Actually|episodelink=Glee, Actually|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Adam Shankman]] (director), Matthew Hodgson (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=December 13, 2012 |season=4 |number=10}}</ref> Though he and Kurt continue to be on good terms, Blaine finds himself developing a crush on his best friend, Sam, which he knows will come to nothing as he knows Sam is not gay; the two of them team up to find evidence that the Warblers cheated at Sectionals, which means New Directions will be competing at Regionals. He ends up going to the Sadie Hawkins dance with [[Tina Cohen-Chang]] ([[Jenna Ushkowitz]]), who has developed a crush on him, but as friends only.<ref name=\"Sadie Hawkins\">{{cite episode |title=Sadie Hawkins|episodelink=Sadie Hawkins (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), Ross Maxwell (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=January 24, 2013 |season=4 |number=11}}</ref> When Kurt comes to Lima for the wedding of glee club director [[Will Schuester|Will]] ([[Matthew Morrison]]) and [[Emma Pillsbury|Emma]] ([[Jayma Mays]])\u2014which Emma flees\u2014he and Blaine make out beforehand, and sleep together afterward, though they do not resume a permanent relationship.<ref name=\"I Do\">{{cite episode |title=I Do|episodelink=I Do (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Brad Falchuk]] (director), [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=February 14, 2013 |season=4 |number=14}}</ref>\n\nBlaine had briefly joined the Cheerios when it looked like New Directions would be disbanding after their Sectionals loss, and cheerleading coach [[Sue Sylvester|Sue]] ([[Jane Lynch]]) blackmails Blaine into rejoining; Blaine and Sam hatch up a plan to bring Sue down from the inside.<ref name=\"Feud\"/> Blaine eventually confesses to Sam that he has feelings for him, to which Sam assures him that he is somewhat flattered by Blaine's honesty and attraction, and that it would not change the fact that Blaine is still Sam's best friend.<ref name=\"Guilty\">{{cite episode |title=Guilty Pleasures|episodelink=Guilty Pleasures (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Eric Stoltz]] (director), [[Russel Friend]] & [[Garrett Lerner]] (writers)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=March 21, 2013 |season=4 |number=17}}</ref> Blaine still loves Kurt and asks Burt for his permission to propose to Kurt, but Burt tells him they're too young to marry, and advises him to wait.<ref name=\"Wonder-ful\">{{cite episode |title=Wonder-ful|episodelink=Wonder-ful|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Wendey Stanzler]] (director), [[Brad Falchuk]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=May 2, 2013 |season=4 |number=21}}</ref> Blaine remains determined, however, and while shopping for a ring, he meets Jan ([[Patty Duke]]), a lesbian jeweler who has been with her partner Liz ([[Meredith Baxter]]) for over thirty years. Jan offers to be a mentor to him, and Blaine and Kurt later have dinner with Jan and Liz, where Jan and Liz explain how their relationship evolved over the years and their experience with the growing mainstream acceptance of gay people.<ref name=\"All or Nothing\"/> New Directions wins at Regionals, and Will and Emma get married immediately afterward, with the glee club, plus some graduates including Kurt, in attendance. Blaine is shown, after the ceremony is over, holding a jewelry box behind his back.<ref name=\"All or Nothing\">{{cite episode |title=All or Nothing|episodelink=All or Nothing (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=May 9, 2013 |season=4 |number=22}}</ref>\n\n===Season 5===\nIn the season premiere, \"[[Love Love Love (Glee)|Love Love Love]]\", Blaine and Kurt agree to be boyfriends again. Blaine still wants to marry Kurt, and stages an elaborate and successful marriage proposal at Dalton Academy where he and Kurt first met, accompanied by New Directions, and all their rival show choir groups, including the Warblers. He auditions for NYADA and is accepted. New Directions comes in second at Nationals, and is disbanded by Sue for not being champions. Blaine graduates as class valedictorian, and then moves to New York to be with Kurt. They start off living together, but though they remain engaged, Blaine ultimately moves out because the two of them realize they still need their own space. The relationship between them goes through rocky patches, including Blaine's insecurity when Kurt becomes popular at school, and when an influential socialite and NYADA supporter hears Blaine perform and takes an interest in his future career, though she is not impressed by Kurt and ultimately tries to break them up, though she fails and ultimately supports them both. Their engagement is strengthened by having weathered these storms, and Blaine moves back in with Kurt.\n\n=== Season 6===\nBlaine returns to Lima after Kurt ended their engagement, having become so despondent that his schoolwork suffered and he was cut by NYADA. He becomes the coach of the Dalton Academy Warblers, and begins dating Dave Karofsky after a chance encounter at the local gay bar. Kurt, having realized he still loves Blaine and regretting that he ended the engagement, arranges for his NYADA off-campus semester to be in Lima, helping Rachel to coach a reinstated New Directions\u2014Will had left McKinley High to coach Vocal Adrenaline. Unfortunately, by the time he arrives, Blaine and Karofsky are already a couple, and there is further strain between Kurt and Blaine as coaches of rival show choirs. In \"[[The Hurt Locker, Part Two]]\", Sue, who \"ships Klaine\" and is desperate for Kurt and Blaine to reunite, locks them both in a fake elevator and refuses to let them leave until they kiss. After resisting for a great many hours, Blaine and Kurt share a passionate kiss, but do not reunite afterward. In \"[[Transitioning (Glee)|Transitioning]]\", Blaine sings a duet with Kurt, \"Somebody Loves You\", and afterward, kisses Kurt. The following day, Blaine, knowing that he is still in love with Kurt, breaks up with Karofsky; however, Kurt is still seeing an older man, Walter. In \"[[A Wedding (Glee)|A Wedding]]\", Kurt tells Walter that he is going to Brittany and Santana's wedding with Blaine, not him, and on Walter's advice, returns to Blaine; the two again become a couple. At the wedding, Brittany insists that Kurt and Blaine get married alongside her and Santana. Though skeptical at first, Kurt and Blaine agree and get married, with Burt officiating the joint ceremony. Dalton Academy burns down in \"[[The Rise and Fall of Sue Sylvester]]\", and the Warblers who transfer to McKinley are accepted into New Directions, with Blaine joining Rachel and Kurt as the coaches of the combined glee club. In the series finale, \"[[Dreams Come True (Glee)|Dreams Come True]]\", after New Directions wins Nationals, Blaine and Kurt leave for New York, with Blaine attending [[New York University|NYU]] and Kurt returning to NYADA along with a reinstated Rachel. The episode jumps ahead to 2020, and Blaine and Kurt are shown to be actors and a celebrity married couple; they also visit schools to entertain and talk about acceptance. Rachel, who is married to Jesse, is pregnant with Blaine and Kurt's child.\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Darren Criss 2011 Shankbone.JPG|thumb|150px|right|Darren Criss (''pictured'') auditioned for ''Glee'' several times before being cast as Blaine.]]\n\n===Casting and creation===\nBlaine is portrayed by actor [[Darren Criss]], who had auditioned for ''Glee'' several times for several roles before the character Blaine was created.<ref name=\"TTO\">{{cite web|url=http://todaysteenonline.com/index.php/2010/11/08/glee-so-who-is-this-darren-criss-guy-and-where-has-he-been-all-my-life/|title=Glee: So Who is this Darren Criss Guy\u2013 And Where Has He Been All My Life?|last=Jacqueline|first=Ilana|date=November 8, 2010|work=Teens Today Online|accessdate=April 20, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110318185459/http://todaysteenonline.com/index.php/2010/11/08/glee-so-who-is-this-darren-criss-guy-and-where-has-he-been-all-my-life/|archivedate=March 18, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He originally auditioned to play [[Finn Hudson]].<ref name=\"Billboard2\">{{cite web|last=Donahue|first=Ann|title={{-'}}Glee' Newcomer Darren Criss Reflects on His 'Dream' Week|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/951040/glee-newcomer-darren-criss-reflects-on-his-dream-week|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 10, 2011|date=November 13, 2010}}</ref> Criss made several audition videos for ''Glee'', of which he posted only one to the social networking website [[MySpace]] where he sang a cover of Bill Withers' song \"[[Lean on Me (song)|Lean on Me]]\". Although the series writers have seen them, he considers them supplemental to his main audition, which was for series creator [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]].<ref name=\"TTO\"/><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/11/09/glee-darren-criss-on-his-guest-role-as-blaine/|title={{-'}}Glee': Darren Criss on His Guest Role as Blaine in 'Never Been Kissed{{'-}}|last=Steinberg|first=Julie|date=November 9, 2010|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> Murphy had not seen any of Criss's previous auditions, but knew he was the right actor for Blaine as soon as he saw this one.<ref name=\"AE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afterelton.com/people/2010/11/glee-ryan-murphy-darren-criss-kurt-hummel |title=Exclusive! \"Glee\"'s Ryan Murphy Discusses Darren Criss, Whether Kurt and Blaine Will Be Boyfriends and More! |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=November 15, 2010 |work=[[AfterEllen.com and AfterElton.com|AfterElton.com]] |publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]] |accessdate=April 21, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505042137/http://www.afterelton.com/people/2010/11/glee-ryan-murphy-darren-criss-kurt-hummel |archivedate=May 5, 2011 |df=mdy}}</ref> The actor cut his long hair before auditioning, to suit the \"serious and preppy\" role.<ref name=\"WSJ\"/>\n\nPrior to the production of season two, rumors circulated that upcoming episodes would feature a love interest for Kurt.<ref name=\"Out\"/> Initial fan and media speculation suggested that [[Sam Evans]] ([[Chord Overstreet]]) was created to fill this role; however, according to Overstreet, Sam's storyline quickly paired him with [[Quinn Fabray]] ([[Dianna Agron]]) as a result of the chemistry the producers detected between him and Agron.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radaronline.com/exclusives/2010/10/audio-glees-chord-overstreet-says-sam-went-gay-straight|title=Audio: Glee's Chord Overstreet Says 'Sam' Went From Gay To Straight|date=October 13, 2010|work=[[RadarOnline]]|accessdate=October 13, 2010}}</ref> In September 2010, it was confirmed that Criss would join the show in a \"much-talked-about new gay role\".<ref name=\"darren criss cast\">{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/09/26/darren-criss-glee-kurt-boyfriend/|title=Scoop:Darren Criss joins 'Glee' as...Kurt's new BF?|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=September 26, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=March 6, 2011}}</ref> Media speculation suggested that Blaine would be Kurt's new love interest.<ref name=\"Out\">{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/slideshows/?slideshow_title=Darren-Criss-The-New-Kid-on-the-Block&theID=1#Top|title=The New Kid on the Block|last=Karpel|first=Ari|work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|publisher=[[Regent Media]]|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> His original character description was: \"a cute and charismatic gay student from a rival Glee club named the Dalton Academy Warblers\u2014will maintain a strictly platonic friendship with McKinley High's most out and proud pupil. But could that change as the season progresses? Yes, it could.\"<ref name=\"darren criss cast\"/> Murphy stated that Blaine's arc would be a significant one. He explained, \"He sort of becomes Kurt's mentor and then maybe love [...] Kurt really admires him and respects him.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.tvsquad.com/2010/09/30/news-roundup-ryan-murphy-confirms-chord-overstreet-will-not-pla/|title= News Roundup: Ryan Murphy Confirms Chord Overstreet Will Not Play Kurt's Boyfriend...|author= Bentley, Jean|work= [[AOL]] TV News|date= September 30, 2010|accessdate= October 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his first few appearances, it was reported that Criss had been confirmed as a series regular for the remainder of season two and for [[Glee (season 3)|season three]] of ''Glee''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/950912/glee-signs-darren-criss-as-series-regular|title=''Glee'' Signs Darren Criss As Series Regular|author=Ann Donahue|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company]]|accessdate=November 15, 2010}}</ref> This was based on comments by Murphy, who said: \"Darren has become such a sensation in one week, which I love. I think there's a hunger for him and a positive relationship role model. He\u2019ll definitely continue through the year and longer.\"<ref name=\"AE\"/> However, the actor later denied that his role had been upgraded and said: \"It's never really been officially confirmed to me. I think the option is there and that they want to keep Blaine around.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1652489/glee-guest-star-darren-criss-not-yet-series-regular.jhtml|title={{-'}}Glee' Guest Star Darren Criss Not Yet A Series Regular|author=Amy Wilkinson|publisher=MTV. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref> Murphy revealed that Blaine may join New Directions during the third season.<ref name=\"prom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/03/glee-scoop-kurt-and-blaine-prom-bound/#more-200615|title=Glee Scoop: Kurt and Blaine Are Prom-Bound!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|author2=Masters, Megan|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Criss hoped that this would not come to pass, as he enjoys being at Dalton Academy, but conceded: \"it's not my call. I'm happy to serve whatever story they want.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/04/ask-ausiello-spoilers-castle-how-i-met-your-mother-big-bang/#more-207140|title=Ask Ausiello: Spoilers on Castle, How I Met Your Mother, Psych, Gossip Girl, Big Bang, and More!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=April 12, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> For the [[Glee (season 3)|third season]] of ''Glee'', Criss was promoted to a series regular,<ref name=CrissShumJr.Regulars>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/07/glee-scoop-chord-overstreet-leaving/|title=Glee Exclusive: Darren Criss and Harry Shum Jr. In, Chord Overstreet Out!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=July 1, 2011|work=[[TV Line]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=July 1, 2011}}</ref> and Blaine did join New Directions when he transferred to McKinley High to be with Kurt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/09/glee-recap-back-to-school-and-basics-in-the-season-3-premiere.html|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: Back to school (and basics) in the Season 3 premiere|first=Amy|last=Reiter|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=September 21, 2011|accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Characterization===\n{{quote box\n|width = 32em\n|border = 1px\n|bgcolor=#c6dbf7\n|fontsize = 85%\n|quote = \"This is the first time I'd really seen an out student that was so young and innocent and really struggling with the big ordeal that it is to be an out student at such an early age. When other shows present the gay character thing, it's typically been in much more adult situations, like gay men living in New York or closeted men who are married and struggling with that ordeal, or having sex on the subway, but never really the core of the journey of defining your sexuality. Blaine offers a beautiful counter to that and makes such a great addition to the many-colored palette that is ''Glee''.\"\n|align = right\n|source = Criss on Blaine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/culture/darren-criss/|title=Darren Criss|last=Mendelson|first=Katie|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|publisher=[[Brant Publications]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref>}}\n\nUpon Blaine's first appearance, Criss described his character as being a \"very charismatic, put-together, composed guy.\" He stated that although Blaine is gay, he is not \"overly [[Effeminacy|queeny]], and not too [[Butch and femme|butch]] either,\" and that while his sexuality is a \"huge part of who he is\", it is not a major facet of how he wishes to be perceived. Due to similarities which stem from their shared sexuality, Blaine \"sees a lot of himself in Kurt, in terms of experiences and the way they feel about the world around them. He feels the need to impart his knowledge, be a source of strength for him, and really help him through what he's going through.\"<ref name=\"kurt's new squeeze\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/online/oscars/2010/11/darren-criss-battled-a-bear-to-get-on-glee-and-now-he-and-the-bear-are-very-good-friends.html|title=Glee\u2019s Darren Criss\u2014Kurt\u2019s New Squeeze?\u2014Describes His Character as \"Tom Ford-ish.\" Perfect!|last=Berk|first=Brett|date=November 9, 2010|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> Initially, Criss felt that the most important element of his character was to give Kurt \"someone he can relate to\", and demonstrate that Kurt could have \"a young out male friend, a support system\".<ref name=\"Out\"/>\n\nCriss discussed his personal connection with Blaine in an interview with ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''. He explained that he grew up among the \"gay community\", being with theater performers, so was raised without a concept of sexuality being an issue. Criss stated that, although he identifies as straight, \"it really doesn't come into play with me in this role. As an actor, your objective is always to play the scene. And this in case, he happens to be a gay teen.\"<ref name=\"kurt's new squeeze\"/> Talk show host and media personality [[Ellen DeGeneres]] deemed Blaine \"a very confident gay teen, which is something you don't see much on television.\"<ref name=\"Ellen Youtube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=649k4tPv8bI|title=Darren Criss sings for Ellen!|date=February 2, 2011|work=The Ellen DeGeneres Show|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> However, Amy Reiter of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' assessed that \"despite the image he projects, he, too, is just a kid trying to figure things out as he goes along.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/02/glee-recap-a-perfect-valentines-day-confection.html|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: A perfect Valentine's Day confection|last=Maerz|first=Melissa|date=February 8, 2011|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> Criss feels that Blaine's confidence is an important aspect of his character, as it is rare for gay teenagers on television to be so \"sure of themselves.\" He hopes that \"all the kids struggling with this issue can look to a guy like Blaine and feel [inspired] by his confidence.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/10/15/glee-darren-criss/|title={{-'}}Glee' Exclusive: Kurt's new (boy)friend speaks!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=October 15, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Relationships===\nThe Kurt\u2013Blaine relationship, sometimes referred to by the [[portmanteau]] \"Klaine\" by ''Glee'' fans and the media,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/02/glee-preview-silly-love-songs/#more-189636|title=Glee Valentine's Episode Preview: Your Burning Questions Answered!|last=Mitovich|first=Matt Webb|date=February 6, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> developed slowly. As the series showrunner, Murphy felt tasked with keeping the two apart as long as possible.<ref name=\"Out\"/> He was initially unsure whether the relationship would become a romantic one, and intended to gauge public response to their friendship before planning future developments. He commented, \"Part of me thinks he should be the boyfriend, part of me thinks he should just be the mentor. I didn't want to decide that until we got into sort of the middle of the season.\"<ref name=\"AE\"/> In December 2010, Colfer said, \"Fans really want it to happen. It's funny how many people want to see these boys hook up. We'll see.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2010/12/glees-chris-colfer-talks-golden-globes-tonsillitis-outbreaks-and-romance-with-blaine/#more-181384|title=Glee's Chris Colfer Talks Golden Globes, Tonsillitis Outbreaks, and Romance with Blaine|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=December 14, 2010|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> Based on the characters' chemistry and the \"immediate outcry\" from fans who wanted to see them as a couple, Murphy decided to have Blaine become Kurt's love interest. Criss noted: \"We all want to see Kurt happy, and like all great love stories, if you have two people that can be together you've got to hold it up.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20460138,00.html#20901379|title=Gay Teens on TV: A Timeline|last=D'Arminio|first=Aubry|date=March 2, 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nConsidering Blaine and Kurt's potential future together, Murphy planned to treat them the same as all other ''Glee'' relationships, by making their pairing \"as flawed and as exposed as everyone else's.\"<ref name=\"Out\"/> This sentiment was re-iterated by executive producer [[Brad Falchuk]], after the characters kissed for the first time. He revealed that their relationship would not run smoothly, and observed that once couples start dating, \"Everything goes to hell.\"<ref name=\"prom\"/> Colfer suggested that Kurt returning to McKinley may cause difficulties in their relationship, but noted \"Distance makes the heart grow fonder, right? That\u2019s what they tell me. So even if they do go through some bumps in the road, it would be very realistic.\"<ref name=\"prom\"/> In a Q&A with [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] on the day \"Born This Way\" ran with Kurt's McKinley return, Criss stated that Blaine and Kurt were \"in the honeymoon stages\" of their relationship, and would still be \"at the end of the [second] season\".<ref name=\"BillboardQA\">{{cite web|title=The Billboard Live Q&A: Darren Criss of \"Glee\", part 3 of 5 (at 6:39)|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/471891/glees-darren-criss-live-qa-video-archive|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 28, 2011|date=April 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a July 2012 interview with ''[[E! News]]'', Colfer said, \"I would like to do something besides say 'I love you,' and I think Darren [Criss] and I agree on that. We're ready for the next step. They've been together for a while. Let's throw some spice and drama into that.\" Colfer quipped that he did not know what was in store for the couple, \"I hear mixed things. I hear they're still together but then maybe they're breaking up.\"<ref name=\"enews\">{{cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/332350/glee-s-chris-colfer-wants-drama-for-kurt-blaine-hopes-to-sing-britney-spears-in-tribute-episode|title=Glee's Chris Colfer Wants \"Drama\" for Kurt & Blaine, Hopes to Sing Britney Spears in Tribute Episode|last=Maldon|first=Mark|date=July 23, 2012|work=[[E! News]]|publisher=[[NBC Universal]]|accessdate= December 26, 2012}}</ref> In September 2012, Criss seconded Colfer, \"We're like an old married couple now. Let's shake it up!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/332350/glee-s-chris-colfer-wants-drama-for-kurt-blaine-hopes-to-sing-britney-spears-in-tribute-episode|title=Glee's Darren Criss Wants Drama for Blaine and Kurt: \"Let's Shake It Up!\"|last=Maldon|first=Mark|date=September 7, 2012|work=E! News|publisher=NBC Universal|accessdate= December 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the second season episode \"Sexy\", Blaine reveals he has a strained relationship with his father.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Sexy|episodelink=Sexy (Glee)|series=Glee |series-link=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] (director), [[Brad Falchuk]] (writer) |network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=March 8, 2011 |season=2 |number=15}}</ref>\n\n==Musical performances==\n[[File:Lea Michele by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Blaine's duet with Rachel (Michele, ''pictured'') marks his only appearance on ''Glee: The Music, Volume 5''.]]\n{{further|Glee discography|List of songs in Glee (season 2)|List of songs in Glee (season 3)|List of songs in Glee (season 4)}}\nAs Blaine, Criss features in many musical performances, which have been released as [[Single (music)|singles]], available for [[Music download|download]]. His first performance, \"[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry song)|Teenage Dream]]\" by [[Katy Perry]], was featured on the soundtrack album ''[[Glee: The Music, Volume 4]]''.<ref name=\"vol4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvsquad.com/2010/11/03/glee-the-music-volume-4-track-listing-released/|title={{-'}}Glee: The Music, Volume 4' Track Listing Released|date=November 3, 2010|first=Jean|last=Bentley|work=TV Squad|publisher=[[AOL]]|accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref> It reached number eight on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in the week ending November 27, 2010,<ref name=\"bill20101127\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-11-27/hot-100?order=gainer|title=Hot 100: Week of November 27, 2010 (Biggest Jump)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> and was the best-selling song in the U.S. that week, selling 214,000 copies: the largest figure for a ''Glee'' title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/e3i156046bdea3250ce85794b3b5746aded|title=A 'Dream' Come True: 'Glee' Cast and Susan Boyle Top Charts|date=November 17, 2010|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> It was only the second U.S.-certified gold single in the show's history.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Glee&format=&go=Search&perPage=50 |title=RIAA Gold & Platinum |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |accessdate=July 15, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130225031458/http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS |archivedate=February 25, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> Both ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'s}} Jillian Mapes and Erica Futterman of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' deemed \"Teenage Dream\" the best song of \"Never Been Kissed\", the episode in which it featured.<ref name=\"JM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/viral-videos/951288/glee-cast-shines-with-katy-perrys-teenage-dream|title={{-'}}Glee' Cast Shines With Katy Perry's 'Teenage Dream{{'-}}|date=November 10, 2010|first=Jillian|last=Mapes|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=November 10, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"EF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/glee-playback-chris-colfer-outshines-the-music-in-never-been-kissed-20101110|title={{-'}}Glee' Playback: Chris Colfer Outshines the Music in 'Never Been Kissed{{'-}}|date=November 10, 2010|first=Erica|last=Futterman|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=November 10, 2010|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/657jB1Y41?url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/glee-playback-chris-colfer-outshines-the-music-in-never-been-kissed-20101110|archive-date=February 1, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]''{{'s}} Anthony Benigno gave the song an \"A\", and noted that it was \"flawless\" and improved on Perry's original.<ref name=\"AB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2010/11/10/2010-11-10_glee_recap_never_been_kissed_introduces_darren_criss_and_gives_dot_jones_her_fir.html|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: 'Never Been Kissed' introduces Darren Criss and gives Dot Jones her first kiss|date=November 10, 2010|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|accessdate=November 10, 2010|location=New York City}}</ref> The performance was nominated for the Best Gay Moment of the Year and Favorite Music Video awards at the 2010 ''[[AfterEllen.com and AfterElton.com|AfterElton.com]]'' Visibility Awards.<ref name=\"AEV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afterelton.com/poll/2010/visibility-awards-winners |title=The AfterElton.com 2010 Visibility Awards&nbsp;\u2013 Winners |last=AfterElton.com Staff |date=December 20, 2010 |work=[[AfterEllen.com and AfterElton.com|AfterElton.com]] |publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]] |accessdate=January 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101065917/http://www.afterelton.com//poll//2010//visibility-awards-winners |archivedate=January 1, 2011 |df= }}</ref> A ''Billboard'' cover-feature on Criss noted that the performance \"arguably ushered in the trend of more current pop hits being reworked by the [''Glee''] cast.\"<ref name=\"MH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/472045/glees-darren-criss-the-billboard-cover-story|title={{-'}}Glee's' Darren Criss: The Billboard Cover Story|last=Herrera|first=Monica|date=April 15, 2011|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nLater songs performed by Blaine and the Warblers became popular enough to warrant a Warbler soundtrack album, ''Glee: The Music Presents the Warblers''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2011/03/08/glees-dalton-warblers-to-release-their-very-own-album/|title=''Glee''{{'s}} Dalton Warblers to Release Their Very Own Album|date=March 8, 2011|first=Elizabeth|last=Tyler|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=[[Time Inc]]|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> The tracks had sold over 1.3&nbsp;million copies as singles by the time the album was released.<ref name=\"holly\">{{Cite web|url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/03/23/glee-warblers-album/|title={{-'}}Glee' News: Warblers Album Tracklisting And Artwork Revealed!|date=March 23, 2011|first=James|last=Dinh|publisher=MTV. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> Blaine performed the lead vocal on covers of [[Train (band)|Train]]'s \"[[Hey, Soul Sister]]\", which peaked at number 32 in Canada,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aolradioblog.com/2010/11/24/glee-special-education-songs-season-2-episode-9/|title={{-'}}Glee' 'Special Education' Songs \u2013 Season 2, Episode 9|date=November 24, 2010|first=Nadina|last=Cheung|publisher=[[AOL Radio]] Blog. [[AOL]]|accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-12-18/canadian-hot-100?order=gainer|title=Canadian Hot 100: Week of December 18, 2010 (Biggest Jump)|date=December 18, 2010|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=December 9, 2010}}</ref> \"[[Bills, Bills, Bills]]\" by [[Destiny's Child]], which reached number 44 in the U.S.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/it_their_way_till_payday_JtT7UKzeKdC22secYRVJYN|title=It's their way, till payday|last=Wieselman|first=Jarett|date=February 3, 2011|work=[[New York Post]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=February 7, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204185715/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/it_their_way_till_payday_JtT7UKzeKdC22secYRVJYN|archive-date=February 4, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Vday\"/> and [[Robin Thicke]]'s \"[[When I Get You Alone]]\", which got to number 47 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"Vday\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/473015/lady-gaga-glee-highlight-historic-hot-100-week|title=Lady Gaga, 'Glee' Highlight Historic Hot 100 Week|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=February 16, 2011|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/12/glee-kurt-and-blaine-sing-when-i-get-you-alone-for-valentines-episode.html |title={{-'}}Glee': Kurt and Blaine sing 'When I Get You Alone' for Valentine's episode |date=December 27, 2010 |first=Hanh |last=Nguyen |publisher=[[Zap2it]]. [[Tribune Media Services]] |accessdate=January 17, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110129075625/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/12/glee-kurt-and-blaine-sing-when-i-get-you-alone-for-valentines-episode.html |archivedate=January 29, 2011 |df= }}</ref> Criss downplayed his performance of \"Bills, Bills, Bills\", and jested that he ought to issue the group's lead singer, [[Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]], an apology for his cover.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/darren-criss-secret-to-meeting-gwyneth-paltrow-on-glee-set-dental-floss_article_46808|title=Darren Criss\u2019 Secret To Meeting Gwyneth Paltrow On 'Glee' Set: Dental Floss|date=April 19, 2011|work=[[Access Hollywood]]|publisher=[[NBC]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Blaine also led on \"[[Silly Love Songs]]\" by [[Wings (band)|Wings]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/01/glee-scoop-from-globes-anne-hathaway-paul-mccartney-a-diva-off-and-more/|title=''Glee'' Scoop From Globes: Anne Hathaway, Paul McCartney, a Diva-Off and More!|date=January 17, 2011|first=Matt Webb|last=Mitovitch|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=January 17, 2011}}</ref> and [[Maroon 5]]'s \"[[Misery (Maroon 5 song)|Misery]]\",<ref name=\"zap16\">{{Cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/03/glee-hear-all-of-the-original-songs-and-covers-from-original-song.html |title={{-'}}Glee': Hear all of the original songs (and covers) from 'Original Song{{'-}} |date=March 11, 2011 |first=Mikey |last=O'Connell |publisher=[[Zap2it]]. [[Tribune Media Services]] |accessdate=March 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110314000303/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/03/glee-hear-all-of-the-original-songs-and-covers-from-original-song.html |archivedate=March 14, 2011 |df= }}</ref> which reached 45 and 52 respectively in the U.S.,<ref name=\"Vday\"/><ref name=\"CB\">{{Cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74345/week-ending-march-20-2011-songs-the-chris-brown-matter/ |title=Week Ending March 20, 2011: Songs: The Chris Brown Matter |date=March 23, 2011 |first=Paul |last=Grein |work=Chart Watch |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]] |accessdate=March 23, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430234208/http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74345/week-ending-march-20-2011-songs-the-chris-brown-matter/ |archivedate=April 30, 2011 |df= }}</ref> and [[Pink (singer)|Pink]]'s \"[[Raise Your Glass]]\", which peaked at number 30 in Australia.<ref name=\"zap16\"/><ref name=\"Aus\">{{Cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Glee+Cast|title=Discography Glee Cast|publisher=australian-charts.com. Hung Medien|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBlaine duetted with Kurt on [[Frank Loesser]]'s \"[[Baby, It's Cold Outside]]\", which was included on ''[[Glee: The Music, The Christmas Album]]'' and reached number 53 in Canada.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/glee-the-music-the-christmas-album--available-november-16-105757288.html|title=Glee: The Music, The Christmas Album \u2212 Available November 16|date=October 26, 2010|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|accessdate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-12-25/canadian-hot-100?order=gainer|title=Canadian Hot 100: Week of December 25, 2010 (Biggest Jump)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=December 16, 2010}}</ref> It was reportedly the most downloaded track of the album, and called \"by far the gayest thing that has ever been on TV\" by Colfer. Murphy expressed his pride in the number for \"push[ing] the envelope a bit.\"<ref name=\"BICO\"/> Jessica Ronayne of ''[[Zap2it]]'' called the duet one of the Christmas episode's few saving graces.<ref name=\"JessicaRonayne\">{{cite web|url=http://tvovermind.zap2it.com/tv-news/glee-season-2-episode-10-glee-christmas-review/40878|title=Glee Season 2 Episode 10 \"A Very Glee Christmas|first=Jessica|last=Ronayne|date=February 8, 2011|work=Zap2it|accessdate=April 15, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211221244/http://tvovermind.zap2it.com/tv-news/glee-season-2-episode-10-glee-christmas-review/40878|archivedate=February 11, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Blaine and Kurt also duetted on [[Neon Trees]]' \"[[Animal (Neon Trees song)|Animal]]\" and [[Hey Monday]]'s \"[[Candles (song)|Candles]]\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/03/glee-listen-to-kurt-and-blaine-perform-neon-trees-animal.html |title={{-'}}Glee': Listen to Kurt and Blaine perform Neon Trees' 'Animal{{'-}} |date=March 4, 2011 |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |publisher=[[Zap2it]]. [[Tribune Media Services]] |accessdate=March 23, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307092349/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/03/glee-listen-to-kurt-and-blaine-perform-neon-trees-animal.html |archivedate=March 7, 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/472501/glees-new-directions-blaine-and-kurt-score-big-at-regionals|title={{-'}}Glee's' New Directions, Blaine and Kurt Score Big at Regionals|date=March 16, 2011|first=Katie|last=Morgan|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|location=New York|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> which peaked at 62 and 71 in the U.S. respectively.<ref name=\"CB\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74342/week-ending-march-13-2011-spears-second-act/ |title=Week Ending March 13, 2011: Spears' Second Act |date=March 16, 2011 |first=Paul |last=Grein |work=Chart Watch |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]] |accessdate=March 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321023907/http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74342/week-ending-march-13-2011-spears-second-act |archivedate=March 21, 2011 }}</ref> In an April 2011 interview, Criss stated that he did not feel established enough within the cast to make song suggestions, but had mentioned liking \"Animal\" to Murphy, who included it in a script soon thereafter.<ref name=\"MH\"/> Blaine shared a duet of \"[[Don't You Want Me]]\" by [[The Human League]] with Rachel, which Reiter deemed a musical highlight of the episode \"[[Blame It on the Alcohol]]\".<ref name= \"amyreiter2\" /> It was included on ''[[Glee: The Music, Volume 5]]'', and peaked at number 44 in Australia.<ref name=\"Aus\"/><ref>{{Cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/glee-debuts-original-songs-on-glee-the-music-volume-5-available-march-8-116643439.html|title=Glee Debuts Original Songs on Glee: The Music, Volume 5 Available March 8|date=February 22, 2011|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|accessdate=February 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of the season, Blaine's musical performances leading the Warblers became so prevalent that he was called out for it on-screen. Criss offered the insight: \"Blaine definitely had his moment in the sun. I think it's time to focus back on the characters that fans of the show really know and love. Completely objectively from watching the show, I was like, 'Why does Blaine get all these songs? This is ridiculous. I want to hear other people doing stuff.' I think we're focusing a little more back on New Directions and taking a little bit of a break from the Warblers.\"<ref name=\"MH\"/>\n\nIn the first episode of [[Glee (season 3)|season three]] of ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', \"[[The Purple Piano Project]]\", Blaine sings \"[[It's Not Unusual]]\" by [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]] when he transfers to McKinley and quits the Warblers for New Directions. After successfully auditioning later in the season for the school's production of ''[[West Side Story]]'' with \"Something's Coming\" from the musical, he sings \"[[Tonight (1956 song)|Tonight]]\" in rehearsal and \"One Hand, One Heart\" in performance, both with his co-star Rachel. He sings lead or co-lead on several songs with New Directions, including \"[[Last Friday Night (T.G.I.F.)]]\"; \"[[Fuckin' Perfect|Perfect]]\" and \"[[Let It Snow! Let It Snow! Let It Snow!]]\" with Kurt; \"[[Control (Janet Jackson song)|Control]]\" and \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\" with Artie and others; and his first original song, the duet \"Extraordinary Merry Christmas\", with Rachel.\n\nIn special tribute episode to [[Michael Jackson]], \"[[Michael (Glee)|Michael]]\", Blaine sings \"[[Wanna Be Startin' Somethin']]\". Futterman wrote that Blaine's \"slick showmanship\" made him a \"natural for lead vocals\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/glee-recap-a-tribute-worthy-of-a-king-20120201 |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: A Tribute Worthy of a King |last=Futterman |first=Erica |date=February 1, 2012 |work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> and ''[[TVLine]]''{{'}}s Michael Slezak called it \"the best use of Darren Criss' voice on Glee in quite some time\" and gave it an \"A\u2212\". ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'s}} Joseph Brannigan Lynch also gave it an \"A\u2212\", and said Criss \"captured the excitement and the spunky bravado of the original\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/glee-michael-jackson-episode/|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: An 'Off the Wall' Tribute to MJ |last=Lynch|first=Joseph Brannigan|date=February 1, 2012|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> [[MTV]]'s Kevin P. Sullivan was another fan of \"the sheer awesomeness of Darren Criss\" on the song, and characterized it as \"a tribute that's more respectful than any other in the episode\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2012/02/01/glee-recap-michael/ |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: 'Michael{{'-}}|date=February 1, 2012|first=Kevin P. |last=Sullivan|work=Hollywood Crush|publisher=[[MTV Networks]]|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref>\nIn the fourteenth episode of the third season, \"[[On My Way (Glee)|On My Way]]\", Blaine performs \"[[Cough Syrup (song)|Cough Syrup]]\" by [[Young the Giant]], which is sung during the [[Dave Karofsky]] suicide sequence. Futterman said Blaine \"flawlessly deliver[ed] the vocal\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/glee-recap-whats-going-on-20120222 |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: What's Going On? |last=Futterman |first=Erica |work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |date=February 22, 2012 |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> Lynch called it a \"chilling rendition\" that was \"hard to shake\" and gave it an {{nowrap|\"A\u2212\",}} the same grade given by Slezak, who wrote, \"taken on its own, Blaine's vocal was strong and passionate\u2014perhaps better than the original\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2012/02/glee-recap-season-3-episode-14-on-my-way-who-won-regionals/|title=''Glee'' Recap: A Very Special Cliffhanger |first=Michael|last=Slezak|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|date=February 21, 2012|accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/glee-season-3-winter-finale-quinn-cliffhanger/|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: To Be Continued... What?! |last=Lynch|first=Joseph Brannigan|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=February 22, 2012|accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> Bobby Hankinson of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' said it was the \"best\" of the episode, and added that the \"scene was really, really well done and carried maximum emotional punch\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.chron.com/tubular/2012/02/glee-gets-serious-real-serious/|title=''Glee'' gets serious. Real serious. |first=Bobby|last=Hankinson|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|publisher=Jack Sweeney|date=February 22, 2012|accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> In the following episode, \"[[Big Brother (Glee)|Big Brother]]\", Blaine shares a duet of [[Gotye]]'s \"[[Somebody That I Used to Know]]\" with his brother Cooper ([[Matt Bomer]]). Crystal Bell of ''[[HuffPost TV]]'' called it the \"highlight of the episode\", and it was Hankinson's favorite performance: \"Bomer and Criss did a fantastic job bringing it to life\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.chron.com/tubular/2012/04/glee-a-master-class-in-handsome-with-blaine-and-cooper/|title=''Glee'': A master class in handsome with Blaine and Cooper |first=Bobby|last=Hankinson|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|publisher=Jack Sweeney|date=April 10, 2012|accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/crystal-bell/glee-recap-big-brother_b_1416019.html |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: Matt Bomer Brings Brotherly Love To McKinley |first=Crystal|last=Bell|work=HuffPost TV|date=April 10, 2012|accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> Futterman said that \"it was initially disconcerting to envision\" two brothers singing about a \"former love\", but she noted that it \"was less weird in context\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/glee-recap-somebody-that-i-used-to-know-20120411 |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: Somebody That I Used to Know |last=Futterman |first=Erica |work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |date=April 11, 2012 |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> In its first week, the cover sold 152,000 digital downloads in the US, and was number twenty-six on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"US\">Peak chart positions for season 3 singles in the United States: \"Somebody That I Used to Know\" and \"Hungry Like the Wolf / Rio\": {{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2012-04-28/hot-100?order=gainer|title=Hot 100: Week of April 28, 2012 (Biggest Jump)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=May 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nBlaine has received mostly positive reviews from television critics. Ellen DeGeneres praised Criss's portrayal, and described him as one of ''Glee''{{'s}} breakout stars.<ref name=\"Ellen Youtube\" /> ''Entertainment Weekly'' named him one of the breakout stars of 2010, with the comment: \"It took about 2 minutes and 11 seconds on ''Glee'' for Darren Criss to turn into a bona fide Gleek phenomenon. [...] And it doesn't hurt that his character Blaine's warm relationship with the show's other openly gay character, Chris Colfer's Kurt, continues to resonate with fans.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20430932_20452138,00.html#20890408|title=16 Breakout Stars of 2010|date=December 20, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> In November 2010, the publication also named Criss the series' best guest-star to date, and praised him for \"seamlessly entering the fold with his charm and great voice.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20302134_20442853,00.html#20877290|title={{-'}}Glee': Ranking the Best Guest Stars|last=Exton|first=Emily|date=November 18, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Ronayne deemed him \"a much better addition to the show than [[Chord Overstreet]]\".<ref name=\"JessicaRonayne\"/> Following his ''Glee'' debut, Criss won the We're Wilde About You Rising Star Award at the 2011 Dorian Awards, presented by the Gay and Lesbian Entertainment Critics Association.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/glee-i-love-score-dorian-72969|title={{-'}}Glee,' 'I Am Love' Score Dorian Awards|last=Kilday|first=Gregg|date=January 18, 2011|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=January 25, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118014169.html?categoryId=13&cs=1|title=Voting deadline for Academy members closing in|last=''Variety'' staff|date=January 21, 2010|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> He also won the 2011 Teen Choice Award for Choice TV Breakout Star.<ref name=\"HolRep\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/teen-choice-awards-2011-winners-220172|title=Teen Choice Awards 2011 Winners Revealed |first=Kimberly |last=Nordyke |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 7, 2011 |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIndecision over his sexuality in the episode \"[[Blame It on the Alcohol]]\" drew some negative reviews of Blaine. Reiter noted that, \"So much of Blaine's charm has been his certainty about who he is.\" Though she found his subplot with Rachel \"fun\", she commented: \"Blaine's overwrought speech in the coffee shop after Rachel asks him out just felt off-key. Saying 'bye' to the Blaine sexual-confusion storyline wouldn't make us angry at all.\"<ref name= \"amyreiter2\">{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/02/glee-recap-making-alcohol-awareness-sing.html|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: Making alcohol awareness sing!|last=Reiter|first=Amy|date=February 22, 2011|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=February 23, 2011}}</ref> Emily VanDerWerff of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' also criticised the storyline, which, she wrote, \"seemed like it might be an interesting, complicated look at teenage [[Human sexuality|sexuality]] and how it can seem formed but might be more fluid than most teens would give it credit for, then lost its nerve and took the easy way out.\"<ref name=\"avclub\">{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/blame-it-on-the-alcohol,52122/ |title=Blame It on the Alcohol |last=VanDerWerff |first=Emily |date=February 22, 2011 |work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> ''AfterElton.com''{{'s}} Chris O'Guinn felt that the only aspect of the storyline handled acceptably was Blaine questioning whether he was bisexual, rather than outright straight. He criticized the shallow examination of his feelings, and wrote: \"Bisexuality is such a contentious issue that it should not be fumbled this way. For a character to say 'maybe I'm bi' in one scene and then the next say, 'nope, definitely gay' is almost cruel in how dismissive it is toward bisexuals by trivializing the intense confusion that many bisexual people feel in coming to terms with their orientation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterelton.com/oysters/03/16/11?page=0%2C1|title=Snails & Oysters: The Bisexual Perspective on ... \"Buffy\" and \"Glee\"|last=O'Guinn|first=Chris|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[AfterEllen.com and AfterElton.com|AfterElton.com]]|publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> In a more positive review, Canning opined that Blaine and Kurt's conversation about sexuality was \"great\". He was \"glad it wasn't an easy talk for either of them\" and said that it \"felt very real for kids in this situation.\"<ref name=\"IGN-BIOTA\">{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/115/1151578p1.html|title=Glee: \"Blame It On the Alcohol\" Review|last=Canning|first=Robert|date=February 23, 2011|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=April 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Chris Colfer 2011 Shankbone.JPG|thumb|right|150px|The relationship between Blaine and Kurt (Colfer, ''pictured'') has been generally well received by critics.]]\nBlaine and Kurt's relationship has been generally well received. They were named Favorite TV Couple at the 2010 ''AfterElton.com'' Visibility Awards,<ref name=\"AEV\"/> and have been lauded for \"leading the way\" in representing gay teenagers on television by ''Entertainment Weekly''.<ref name=\"BICO\">{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/01/20/glee-gay-teens-ew-cover/|title=This week's cover: How 'Glee' is leading TV's gay-teen revolution|date=January 20, 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Jarett Wieselman of the ''[[New York Post]]'' referred to them as \"one of the most beloved TV couples of the millennium\".<ref name=\"NYP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/chris_colfer_8cb1mvxH33ELSaIhQEza5O |title=It's Chris Colfer's Time |last=Wieselman |first=Jarett |date=April 21, 2011 |work=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=April 21, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424033957/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/chris_colfer_8cb1mvxH33ELSaIhQEza5O |archivedate=April 24, 2011 |df= }}</ref> When they \"finally solidified what their relationship actually is\" in the episode \"[[Silly Love Songs (Glee)|Silly Love Songs]]\", ''[[IGN]]''{{'s}} Robert Canning noted that his opinion of Blaine improved. He commented: \"I love that the [serenading of Jeremiah] blew up in Blaine's face. The character has always come off to me as annoyingly arrogant, but \"Silly Love Songs\" humanized the guy. Guess I may have to like him now.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/114/1148604p1.html|title=Glee: \"Silly Love Songs\" Review|last=Canning|first=Robert|date=February 8, 2011|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> Their first kiss, in the episode \"[[Original Song]]\", was met with critical acclaim. Mark Perigard of ''[[The Boston Herald]]'' wrote, \"It was utterly, sweetly romantic, and Criss sold the hell out of the moment. It's long overdue and it will silence the growing legion of critics out there who were unhappy with the pace of this story.\"<ref name=\"BostonH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/blogs/entertainment/love_that_tv/?p=484|title={{-'}}Glee': Klaine takes off, Rachel hits bottom|last=Perigard|first=Mark|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[Boston Herald]]|publisher=Herald Media Inc.|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} Mandi Bierly was so impressed with the scene that she was initially concerned it may be a dream sequence, \"because we don't get romantic, unapologetic first kisses like that between young gay characters on network TV.\" She wrote, \"Relationships aren't easy. They\u2019ll make mistakes. But if they stay true to themselves, and continue to be as open and honest with each other, we're in for something special.\"<ref name=\"MB\">{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/03/16/glee-kurt-blaine-kiss/|title={{-'}}Glee': Anyone else think that dreamy Blaine/Kurt moment had to be a dream?|last=Bierly|first=Mandi|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Kevin Fallon of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' thought the kiss was \"sweet\", and stated that he was pleased that it attracted no controversy whatsoever.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2011/03/on-glee-two-boys-kiss-without-controversy/72571/|title=On 'Glee,' Two Boys Kiss, Without Controversy|last=Fallon|first=Kevin|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> Aly Semigran of MTV praised the interaction between Blaine and Kurt. She called the kiss scene a \"sweet, real and, shockingly, un-hyped moment\", and praised Criss and Colfer for \"handl[ing] it with dignity and honesty\".<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/03/16/glee-recap-original-song/|title=Glee Recap Original Song|last=Semigran|first=Aly|date=March 16, 2011|publisher=MTV. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhile Lesley Goldberg of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' was pleased Blaine's season three transfer to McKinley in the first episode increased Criss' screen time with Colfer and the New Directions cast, she stated that the move \"screams of co-dependency.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/glee-season-3-premiere-hits-238003|title={{-'}}Glee' Season 3 Premiere: Hits and Misses|first=Lesley|last=Goldberg|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=September 20, 2011|accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref> In contrast, ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} Abby West found it romantic, and noted: \"Blaine and Kurt, with their budding love and witty, pseudo-urbane ways, are my favorite couple to watch. ... I look forward to hearing [Blaine] sing more, watching him bump up against the insular Glee clubbers, and seeing him show off his non-uniform attire\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/glee-season-3-episode-1-purple-piano-project/|title={{-'}}Glee' season premiere recap: Join the Club!|first=Abby|last=West|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|date=September 21, 2011|accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref> Several reviewers were unhappy with the second episode's revelation that Blaine was a junior, not a senior like Kurt, as had been implied in the previous season. VanDerWerff wrote that Blaine \"seems to have simultaneously gotten younger and had a complete personality transplant over the summer\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'s}} Rae Votta noted \"the continuity-bending plot point that he's somehow a Junior and not a Senior like his boyfriend\", and Samantha Urban of ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' allowed her exasperation to show: \"Oh really, ''Glee''? Blaine's a junior? Blaine's younger than Kurt? Fine. FINE.\"<ref name=\"AV302\">{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/i-am-unicorn,62295/|title={{-\"}}I Am Unicorn{{\"-}}|first=Emily|last=VanDerWerff|date=September 27, 2011|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"BBRV302\">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/467229/glee-has-mommy-issues-in-plot-aplenty-episode|title={{-'}}Glee' Has Mommy Issues in Plot-Aplenty Episode|first=Rae|last=Votta|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=September 28, 2011|accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Dallas302\">{{Cite web|url=http://popcultureblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2011/09/tv-recap-glee---i-am-unicorn.html |title=TV recap: \"Glee\" \u2013 'I Am Unicorn{{'-}} |date=September 28, 2011 |first=Samantha |last=Urban |work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |accessdate=September 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003210756/http://popcultureblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2011/09/tv-recap-glee---i-am-unicorn.html |archivedate=October 3, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\nKurt and Blaine make the decision to have sex for the first time in \"[[The First Time (Glee)|The First Time]]\" episode; many critics were enthusiastic about the fact that a gay couple was being given such a storyline. Canning said that Kurt and Blaine's \"attempts to get a little wild\", and \"trying to grow up faster than they should\", were \"the better parts of the episode as they felt the most realistic\".<ref name=\"IGN-TheFirstTime\">{{cite web |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/121/1212004p1.html |title=Glee: \"The First Time\" Review |last=Canning |first=Robert |date=November 9, 2011 |work=IGN |publisher=News Corporation|accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref> Futterman praised their departure from the bar as a \"very faithful and honest scene\".<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/glee-recap-the-first-time-tries-too-hard-20111109 |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: 'The First Time' Tries Too Hard |last=Futterman |first=Erica |date=November 9, 2011 |work=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref> VanDerWerff and [[BuddyTV]] contributor John Kubicek both had issues with Blaine's characterization. The latter asserted that he \"just behaves however the writers need him to behave in order for the scene to work\", while the former said that Blaine's season three storyline \"hasn\u2019t been bad by any means, but it does feel like Darren Criss is playing someone who\u2019s quite a bit different from the guy he was playing last season\".<ref name=\"Buddy\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/glee/glee-recap-the-agony-of-sex-42559.aspx|title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: The Agony of Sex|date=November 8, 2011|first=John|last=Kubicek|publisher=BuddyTV|accessdate=November 23, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110112426/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/glee/glee-recap-the-agony-of-sex-42559.aspx|archive-date=November 10, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bell was impressed by the way the characters' relationship \"inspires gay youth in a way that we haven't seen on network television yet\" and called them \"amazing role models for all teens\", and ''The Atlantic'' writer Kevin Fallon said it was \"remarkable\" and a \"milestone\" that \"the decision by gay teen characters to lose their virginities is given equal weight to that of a straight couple\".<ref name=\"ATL\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/11/how-glee-got-teen-sex-right/248157/ |title=How 'Glee' Got Teen Sex Right |date=November 9, 2011 |last1=Fallon |first1=Kevin |work=The Atlantic |publisher=Atlantic Media Company|accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDiscussing public response to his character, Criss stated that he particularly enjoyed comments from \"people from parts of the world who are maybe not as exposed to certain ideologies\", but had reconsidered their stance on relationships and human rights as a result of the Blaine\u2013Kurt storyline. He called this response \"phenomenal\", and said: \"I was a straight kid growing up in a very gay community and it's something that I've had to watch so many friends have to struggle with and have no place to go to identify in kind of a grander media culture. To be a small piece of that machine is incredibly wonderful.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterelton.com/people/2011/01/darren-criss-glee-teenage-dream?page=0%2C1|title=Interview: Darren Criss Humbly Calls Himself \"Last Grain of Sand{{\"-}}|last=Jensen|first=Michael|date=January 18, 2011|work=[[AfterEllen.com and AfterElton.com|AfterElton.com]]|publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]|accessdate=April 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Glee}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Blaine}}\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2010]]\n[[Category:Fictional gay males]]\n[[Category:Fictional LGBT characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional singers]]\n[[Category:Glee (TV series) characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional pianists]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the federal judge|J. Blaine Anderson}}\n{{short description|Fictional character from the Fox series Glee}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name = Blaine Anderson\n| image = Blaine Glee Tour Silly.jpg\n| caption = [[Darren Criss]] as Blaine Anderson during [[Glee Live! In Concert!]]\n| series = [[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]\n| first = \"[[Never Been Kissed (Glee)|Never Been Kissed]]\"\n| last = \"[[Dreams Come True (Glee)|Dreams Come True]]\"\n| portrayer = [[Darren Criss]]\n| occupation = student, singer, glee club director, actor\n| creator = [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]]<br/>[[Brad Falchuk]]<br/>[[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]]\n| spouse = [[Kurt Hummel]] (husband)\n| family = Pam Anderson (mother)<br />Cooper Anderson (brother)<br>Unnamed Daughter\n| significant_other = [[Rachel Berry]] (one off relationship, ex-girlfriend)<br>[[Dave Karofsky]] (ex-boyfriend)\n}}\n'''Blaine Devon Anderson'''<ref name=\"Feud\">{{cite episode |title=Feud|episodelink=Feud (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=March 14, 2013 |season=4 |number=16}}</ref> is a fictional character from the American musical comedy-drama television series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]''. Played by [[Darren Criss]], Blaine was introduced in the [[Never Been Kissed (Glee)|sixth episode]] of the [[Glee (season 2)|second season]] as the [[openly gay]] lead singer of the Dalton Academy Warblers, a rival show choir to New Directions, the show's primary musical group. Blaine initially served as a mentor for New Directions member [[Kurt Hummel]] ([[Chris Colfer]]). Chemistry between the two, combined with fan support for the couple, led series co-creator [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] to pair them romantically. Their relationship has been well received by critics, and they have been named \"one of the most beloved TV couples of the millennium\" by Jarett Wieselman of the ''[[New York Post]]''.<ref name=\"NYP\"/> At the beginning of the third season, Blaine transfers to McKinley High and joins New Directions; concurrently, Criss was promoted from recurring guest star to the show's main cast.\n\nCriss auditioned for ''Glee'' several times before being cast as Blaine, including for the lead role of [[Finn Hudson]]. He believed he would be ill-suited to that character, but identifies with Blaine, having been raised among the \"gay community\".<ref name=\"kurt's new squeeze\"/> He plays Blaine as charismatic and confident, and finds his youthful self-acceptance a fitting counterpoint to common media portrayals of gay characters.\n\nAs the Warblers' lead vocalist and subsequent New Directions member, Blaine has performed a number of songs on the television series. His first, a [[cover version]] of \"[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry song)|Teenage Dream]]\" by [[Katy Perry]], became the fastest-selling ''Glee'' single, reached number eight on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and was certified gold in the U.S.<ref name=\"bill20101127\"/><ref name=\"riaa\"/> Tracks by the Warblers have sold over 1.3&nbsp;million copies. The songs became popular enough to warrant a Warbler soundtrack album, ''[[Glee: The Music Presents the Warblers]]''. Blaine has received mostly positive reviews from critics; Criss has been awarded a Rising Star accolade from the Gay and Lesbian Entertainment Critics Association for his portrayal. While the Blaine\u2013Kurt (\"Klaine\") relationship has been met with acclaim, an episode storyline in which Blaine questioned his sexuality attracted negative reviews for undermining his previous characterization as a confident gay teenager.\n\n==Storylines==\n===Season 2===\nBlaine Anderson is introduced in the episode \"[[Never Been Kissed (Glee)|Never Been Kissed]]\" as the lead soloist of the Dalton Academy Warblers [[a cappella]] musical group, and honestly changed Glee for the better. He meets [[Kurt Hummel]] ([[Chris Colfer]]), a member of the rival [[glee club]] New Directions. When Kurt asks if Blaine is gay, Blaine matter-of-factly says he is; Kurt tells Blaine that he is being bullied at school for being gay, and Blaine reveals that he too was harassed at his old school, so he transferred to Dalton Academy, which enforces a no-bullying policy. Blaine befriends Kurt, and helps him stand up to his tormentor, [[Dave Karofsky]] ([[Max Adler (actor)|Max Adler]]).<ref name=\"NY\">{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/11/glee_recap_teenage_dream.html|title=Glee Recap: Teenage Dream|date=November 10, 2010|first=Rebecca|last=Milzoff|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|publisher=New York Media Holdings|accessdate=November 10, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN-NeverBeenKissed\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/113/1133366p1.html|title=Glee: \"Never Been Kissed\" Review|date=November 10, 2010|first=Robert|last=Canning|publisher=IGN|accessdate=November 10, 2010}}</ref> When the threats and violence against Kurt reach a dangerous level, he transfers to Dalton Academy.<ref>{{cite web|first=Robert|last=Canning|url=http://au.tv.ign.com/articles/113/1136637p1.html|accessdate=2011-01-02|title=Glee: \"Furt\" Review&nbsp;\u2014 TV Review at IGN|work=[[IGN]]|date=November 24, 2010}}</ref> He falls in love with Blaine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2010/12/glee-review-a-very-glee-christmas/|title=Glee Review: You're a Sweet One, Sue the Grinch|work=TV Fanatic|first=Matt|last=Richenthal|date=December 8, 2010|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> who is initially oblivious to Kurt's feelings even as their friendship grows. Blaine enlists Kurt's help to serenade his crush Jeremiah (Alexander Nifong), the assistant manager at a local Gap store. Jeremiah is subsequently fired and rebuffs Blaine. Kurt confesses his feelings, and Blaine tells Kurt that he cares for him, but is terrible at romance and does not want to risk damaging their friendship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2011/02/glee-review-silly-love-songs/|title=Glee Review: Lots of Luck, Santana|last=Richenthal|first=Matt|date=February 8, 2011|work=TV Fanatic|accessdate=February 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nKurt and Blaine attend a party hosted by New Directions co-captain [[Rachel Berry]] ([[Lea Michele]]). The attendees play [[spin the bottle]], which results in Rachel and Blaine kissing. In the aftermath, Blaine wonders whether he might be bisexual, and goes on a date with Rachel. When she kisses him again while they are both sober, he concludes that he is indeed gay, which relieves Kurt.<ref name=\"sc\">{{cite web|url=http://screencrave.com/2011-02-23/glee-season-2-episode-14-blame-it-on-the-alcohol-tv-review/|title=Glee: Season 2 Episode 14: Blame It On the Alcohol -TV Review|last=Butler|first=Candace|date=February 22, 2011|work=ScreenCrave|accessdate=February 23, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022431/http://screencrave.com/2011-02-23/glee-season-2-episode-14-blame-it-on-the-alcohol-tv-review/|archivedate=July 16, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter learning of Kurt\u2019s ignorance of sexual matters, Blaine visits Kurt's father, [[Burt Hummel|Burt]] ([[Mike O'Malley]]), and prompts him to give Kurt \"[[the birds and the bees|the talk]]\" about sex.<ref name=\"Sexy\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/03/09/glee-season-2-episode-15-sexy-tv-recap/?mod=google_news_blog|title={{-'}}Glee' Season 2, Episode 15 'Sexy': TV Recap|last=Flandez|first=Raymund|date=March 9, 2011|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|accessdate=March 9, 2011}}</ref> As the Warblers prepare to perform at the Regional show choir competition, Kurt admits that he is jealous of how many solos Blaine gets. At a subsequent group meeting, Kurt arrives late and announces that the group's mascot canary is dead; he sings \"[[Blackbird (Beatles song)|Blackbird]]\" in honor of the bird. While Kurt is singing, Blaine has a revelation, and later tells Kurt that he reciprocates his feelings and kisses him. At Regionals, the two sing a duet of \"Candles\" by [[Hey Monday]]. The Warblers lose to New Directions, but while Kurt is very disappointed, Blaine tells him that even though they lost, in reality, they won each other which makes losing Regionals worth it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2011/03/16/2011-03-16_glee_season_2_episode_16_kurt_and_blaine_kiss_in_midst_of_original_song_tracks.html|title={{-'}}Glee' Season 2, Episode 16 'Original Song: TV Recap|last=Flandez|first=Raymund|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|accessdate=March 17, 2011}}</ref> After Kurt transfers back to McKinley, he invites Blaine to be his date at his junior prom in \"[[Prom Queen (Glee)|Prom Queen]]\"; both are shocked when Kurt wins Prom Queen due to having received an overwhelming number of unwanted write-in votes in the secret balloting. Karofsky, the Prom King, leaves to avoid dancing with a guy in the traditional dance between King and Queen, and Kurt dances with Blaine instead.<ref name=\"Prom Queen\">{{cite episode |title=Prom Queen |episodelink=Prom Queen (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Ian Brennan (writer), Eric Stoltz (director)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=May 10, 2011 |season=2 |number=20}}</ref> After Kurt returns from Nationals in New York, he and Blaine admit their love for one another.<ref name=\"New York\">{{cite episode |title=New York |episodelink=New York (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Brad Falchuk (director, writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=May 24, 2011 |season=2 |number=22}}</ref>\n\n===Season 3===\nIn the first episode of the [[Glee (season 3)|third season]], \"[[The Purple Piano Project]]\", Blaine transfers to McKinley High at the beginning of his junior year to be closer to Kurt, who is a senior, and joins New Directions.<ref name=\"Purple\">{{cite episode |title=The Purple Piano Project|episodelink=The Purple Piano Project|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Eric Stoltz]] (director), [[Brad Falchuk]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=September 20, 2011 |season=3 |number=1}}</ref> He later auditions for the role of Bernardo in the school musical ''[[West Side Story]]'', so as not to compete against Kurt who wants to play the male lead, Tony, but is cast as Tony himself.<ref name=\"Unicorn\">{{cite episode |title=I Am Unicorn|episodelink=I Am Unicorn|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Brad Falchuk]] (director), [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=September 27, 2011 |season=3 |number=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Asian F\">{{cite episode |title=Asian F|episodelink=Asian F|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Alfonso Gomez-Rejon]] (director), [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=October 4, 2011 |season=3 |number=3}}</ref> In the episode \"[[The First Time (Glee)|The First Time]]\", Blaine is pursued by [[Sebastian Smythe]] ([[Grant Gustin]]), a new Dalton Academy Warbler. Kurt and Blaine meet up with Sebastian at a gay bar, Blaine gets drunk, and afterward tries to get Kurt to have sex with him in the car. Kurt refuses, they have a fight, and Blaine decides to walk home. After the ''West Side Story'' opening night, they apologize to each other, and decide to go to Blaine's house. They are later shown in bed together, apparently having just had sex for the first time.<ref name=\"First Time\">{{cite episode |title=The First Time|episodelink=The First Time (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=November 8, 2011 |season=3 |number=5}}</ref> When New Directions and the Warblers informally compete in \"[[Michael (Glee)|Michael]]\" to determine which club can perform [[Michael Jackson]]'s music at the upcoming show choir Regionals, Sebastian throws a slushie containing rock salt at Kurt, but Blaine interposes himself and is hit in the eye; his cornea is badly scratched and requires surgery.<ref name=\"Michael\">{{cite episode |title=Michael|episodelink=Michael (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Alfonso Gomez-Rejon]] (director), [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=January 31, 2012 |season=3 |number=11}}</ref> His eye heals, and he is back in time for New Directions to defeat the Warblers at Regionals.<ref name=\"On My Way\">{{cite episode |title=On My Way|episodelink=On My Way (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=February 21, 2012 |season=3 |number=14}}</ref> Blaine's older brother Cooper ([[Matt Bomer]]), a successful actor in commercials, visits Ohio, and the two achieve a rapprochement.<ref name=\"Big Brother\">{{cite episode |title=Big Brother|episodelink=Big Brother (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Eric Stoltz]] (director), [[Michael Hitchcock]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=April 10, 2012 |season=3 |number=15}}</ref> Blaine's relationship with Kurt is later strained when Kurt text-flirts with a boy he met while preparing for his NYADA audition, and by Kurt's eagerness to leave for New York after graduation, which would separate the two at least until Blaine graduated the following year.<ref name=\"Dance with Somebody\">{{cite episode |title=Dance with Somebody|episodelink=Dance with Somebody (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Paris Barclay]] (director), Ross Maxwell (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=April 24, 2012 |season=3 |number=17}}</ref> The two patch things up, the glee club wins at Nationals, and the pair is still a couple at the end of the school year, though Blaine is still uneasy about the prolonged physical separation facing them.<ref name=\"Goodbye\">{{cite episode |title=Goodbye|episodelink=Goodbye (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Brad Falchuk]] (director, writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=May 22, 2012 |season=3 |number=22}}</ref>\n\n===Season 4===\nIn the first episode of the [[Glee (season 4)|fourth season]], \"[[The New Rachel]]\", Blaine becomes the lead singer of New Directions and successfully prompts Kurt to follow his New York City dreams.<ref name=\"New Rachel\">{{cite episode |title=The New Rachel|episodelink=The New Rachel|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Brad Falchuk]] (director), [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=September 13, 2012 |season=4 |number=1}}</ref> In addition, Blaine successfully runs for senior class president with [[Sam Evans|Sam]] ([[Chord Overstreet]]), and the two subsequently develop a friendship.<ref name=\"Makeover\">{{cite episode |title=Makeover |episodelink=Makeover (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Eric Stoltz]] (director), [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]] (writer) |network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=September 27, 2012 |season=4 |number=3}}</ref> Kurt inadvertently pulls away from Blaine due to his Vogue.com internship; distraught and feeling isolated from his friends, Blaine cheats on Kurt.<ref name=\"Makeover\"/><ref name=\"Break Up\">{{cite episode |title=The Break Up|episodelink=The Break Up (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Alfonso Gomez-Rejon]] (director), [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=October 4, 2012 |season=4 |number=4}}</ref> After confessing to Kurt of his infidelity, Kurt severs all ties.<ref name=\"Break Up\"/> New Directions' Nationals trophy is stolen by Hunter Clarington ([[Nolan Gerard Funk]]), the new captain of the Dalton Academy Warblers.<ref name=\"Dynamic\">{{cite episode |title=Dynamic Duets |episodelink=Dynamic Duets|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]] (writer and director) |network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=November 22, 2012 |season=4 |number=7}}</ref> When Blaine goes to Dalton Academy to retrieve it, Hunter and Sebastian attempt to seduce Blaine into returning to the Warblers. Blaine becomes conflicted, believing that he does not belong in New Directions.<ref name=\"Dynamic\"/> Sam ultimately convinces him that, despite having done a bad thing to Kurt, Blaine is still a good person and an important member of New Directions.<ref name=\"Dynamic\"/>\n\nKurt begins to mend their relationship in \"[[Thanksgiving (Glee)|Thanksgiving]]\", just before New Directions loses at Sectionals to the Warblers, and they spend Christmas together in New York City.<ref name=\"Thanksgiving\">{{cite episode |title=Thanksgiving|episodelink=Thanksgiving (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), [[Russel Friend]] & [[Garrett Lerner]] (writers)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=November 29, 2012 |season=4 |number=8}}</ref><ref name=\"Actually\">{{cite episode |title=Glee, Actually|episodelink=Glee, Actually|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Adam Shankman]] (director), Matthew Hodgson (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=December 13, 2012 |season=4 |number=10}}</ref> Though he and Kurt continue to be on good terms, Blaine finds himself developing a crush on his best friend, Sam, which he knows will come to nothing as he knows Sam is not gay; the two of them team up to find evidence that the Warblers cheated at Sectionals, which means New Directions will be competing at Regionals. He ends up going to the Sadie Hawkins dance with [[Tina Cohen-Chang]] ([[Jenna Ushkowitz]]), who has developed a crush on him, but as friends only.<ref name=\"Sadie Hawkins\">{{cite episode |title=Sadie Hawkins|episodelink=Sadie Hawkins (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), Ross Maxwell (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=January 24, 2013 |season=4 |number=11}}</ref> When Kurt comes to Lima for the wedding of glee club director [[Will Schuester|Will]] ([[Matthew Morrison]]) and [[Emma Pillsbury|Emma]] ([[Jayma Mays]])\u2014which Emma flees\u2014he and Blaine make out beforehand, and sleep together afterward, though they do not resume a permanent relationship.<ref name=\"I Do\">{{cite episode |title=I Do|episodelink=I Do (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Brad Falchuk]] (director), [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=February 14, 2013 |season=4 |number=14}}</ref>\n\nBlaine had briefly joined the Cheerios when it looked like New Directions would be disbanding after their Sectionals loss, and cheerleading coach [[Sue Sylvester|Sue]] ([[Jane Lynch]]) blackmails Blaine into rejoining; Blaine and Sam hatch up a plan to bring Sue down from the inside.<ref name=\"Feud\"/> Blaine eventually confesses to Sam that he has feelings for him, to which Sam assures him that he is somewhat flattered by Blaine's honesty and attraction, and that it would not change the fact that Blaine is still Sam's best friend.<ref name=\"Guilty\">{{cite episode |title=Guilty Pleasures|episodelink=Guilty Pleasures (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Eric Stoltz]] (director), [[Russel Friend]] & [[Garrett Lerner]] (writers)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=March 21, 2013 |season=4 |number=17}}</ref> Blaine still loves Kurt and asks Burt for his permission to propose to Kurt, but Burt tells him they're too young to marry, and advises him to wait.<ref name=\"Wonder-ful\">{{cite episode |title=Wonder-ful|episodelink=Wonder-ful|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Wendey Stanzler]] (director), [[Brad Falchuk]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=May 2, 2013 |season=4 |number=21}}</ref> Blaine remains determined, however, and while shopping for a ring, he meets Jan ([[Patty Duke]]), a lesbian jeweler who has been with her partner Liz ([[Meredith Baxter]]) for over thirty years. Jan offers to be a mentor to him, and Blaine and Kurt later have dinner with Jan and Liz, where Jan and Liz explain how their relationship evolved over the years and their experience with the growing mainstream acceptance of gay people.<ref name=\"All or Nothing\"/> New Directions wins at Regionals, and Will and Emma get married immediately afterward, with the glee club, plus some graduates including Kurt, in attendance. Blaine is shown, after the ceremony is over, holding a jewelry box behind his back.<ref name=\"All or Nothing\">{{cite episode |title=All or Nothing|episodelink=All or Nothing (Glee)|series=Glee |serieslink=Glee (TV series) |credits=Bradley Buecker (director), [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]] (writer)|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=May 9, 2013 |season=4 |number=22}}</ref>\n\n===Season 5===\nIn the season premiere, \"[[Love Love Love (Glee)|Love Love Love]]\", Blaine and Kurt agree to be boyfriends again. Blaine still wants to marry Kurt, and stages an elaborate and successful marriage proposal at Dalton Academy where he and Kurt first met, accompanied by New Directions, and all their rival show choir groups, including the Warblers. He auditions for NYADA and is accepted. New Directions comes in second at Nationals, and is disbanded by Sue for not being champions. Blaine graduates as class valedictorian, and then moves to New York to be with Kurt. They start off living together, but though they remain engaged, Blaine ultimately moves out because the two of them realize they still need their own space. The relationship between them goes through rocky patches, including Blaine's insecurity when Kurt becomes popular at school, and when an influential socialite and NYADA supporter hears Blaine perform and takes an interest in his future career, though she is not impressed by Kurt and ultimately tries to break them up, though she fails and ultimately supports them both. Their engagement is strengthened by having weathered these storms, and Blaine moves back in with Kurt.\n\n=== Season 6===\nBlaine returns to Lima after Kurt ended their engagement, having become so despondent that his schoolwork suffered and he was cut by NYADA. He becomes the coach of the Dalton Academy Warblers, and begins dating Dave Karofsky after a chance encounter at the local gay bar. Kurt, having realized he still loves Blaine and regretting that he ended the engagement, arranges for his NYADA off-campus semester to be in Lima, helping Rachel to coach a reinstated New Directions\u2014Will had left McKinley High to coach Vocal Adrenaline. Unfortunately, by the time he arrives, Blaine and Karofsky are already a couple, and there is further strain between Kurt and Blaine as coaches of rival show choirs. In \"[[The Hurt Locker, Part Two]]\", Sue, who \"ships Klaine\" and is desperate for Kurt and Blaine to reunite, locks them both in a fake elevator and refuses to let them leave until they kiss. After resisting for a great many hours, Blaine and Kurt share a passionate kiss, but do not reunite afterward. In \"[[Transitioning (Glee)|Transitioning]]\", Blaine sings a duet with Kurt, \"Somebody Loves You\", and afterward, kisses Kurt. The following day, Blaine, knowing that he is still in love with Kurt, breaks up with Karofsky; however, Kurt is still seeing an older man, Walter. In \"[[A Wedding (Glee)|A Wedding]]\", Kurt tells Walter that he is going to Brittany and Santana's wedding with Blaine, not him, and on Walter's advice, returns to Blaine; the two again become a couple. At the wedding, Brittany insists that Kurt and Blaine get married alongside her and Santana. Though skeptical at first, Kurt and Blaine agree and get married, with Burt officiating the joint ceremony. Dalton Academy burns down in \"[[The Rise and Fall of Sue Sylvester]]\", and the Warblers who transfer to McKinley are accepted into New Directions, with Blaine joining Rachel and Kurt as the coaches of the combined glee club. In the series finale, \"[[Dreams Come True (Glee)|Dreams Come True]]\", after New Directions wins Nationals, Blaine and Kurt leave for New York, with Blaine attending [[New York University|NYU]] and Kurt returning to NYADA along with a reinstated Rachel. The episode jumps ahead to 2020, and Blaine and Kurt are shown to be actors and a celebrity married couple; they also visit schools to entertain and talk about acceptance. Rachel, who is married to Jesse, is pregnant with Blaine and Kurt's child.\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Darren Criss 2011 Shankbone.JPG|thumb|150px|right|Darren Criss (''pictured'') auditioned for ''Glee'' several times before being cast as Blaine.]]\n\n===Casting and creation===\nBlaine is portrayed by actor [[Darren Criss]], who had auditioned for ''Glee'' several times for several roles before the character Blaine was created.<ref name=\"TTO\">{{cite web|url=http://todaysteenonline.com/index.php/2010/11/08/glee-so-who-is-this-darren-criss-guy-and-where-has-he-been-all-my-life/|title=Glee: So Who is this Darren Criss Guy\u2013 And Where Has He Been All My Life?|last=Jacqueline|first=Ilana|date=November 8, 2010|work=Teens Today Online|accessdate=April 20, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110318185459/http://todaysteenonline.com/index.php/2010/11/08/glee-so-who-is-this-darren-criss-guy-and-where-has-he-been-all-my-life/|archivedate=March 18, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He originally auditioned to play [[Finn Hudson]].<ref name=\"Billboard2\">{{cite web|last=Donahue|first=Ann|title={{-'}}Glee' Newcomer Darren Criss Reflects on His 'Dream' Week|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/951040/glee-newcomer-darren-criss-reflects-on-his-dream-week|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 10, 2011|date=November 13, 2010}}</ref> Criss made several audition videos for ''Glee'', of which he posted only one to the social networking website [[MySpace]] where he sang a cover of Bill Withers' song \"[[Lean on Me (song)|Lean on Me]]\". Although the series writers have seen them, he considers them supplemental to his main audition, which was for series creator [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]].<ref name=\"TTO\"/><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/11/09/glee-darren-criss-on-his-guest-role-as-blaine/|title={{-'}}Glee': Darren Criss on His Guest Role as Blaine in 'Never Been Kissed{{'-}}|last=Steinberg|first=Julie|date=November 9, 2010|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> Murphy had not seen any of Criss's previous auditions, but knew he was the right actor for Blaine as soon as he saw this one.<ref name=\"AE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afterelton.com/people/2010/11/glee-ryan-murphy-darren-criss-kurt-hummel |title=Exclusive! \"Glee\"'s Ryan Murphy Discusses Darren Criss, Whether Kurt and Blaine Will Be Boyfriends and More! |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=November 15, 2010 |work=[[AfterEllen.com and AfterElton.com|AfterElton.com]] |publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]] |accessdate=April 21, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505042137/http://www.afterelton.com/people/2010/11/glee-ryan-murphy-darren-criss-kurt-hummel |archivedate=May 5, 2011 |df=mdy}}</ref> The actor cut his long hair before auditioning, to suit the \"serious and preppy\" role.<ref name=\"WSJ\"/>\n\nPrior to the production of season two, rumors circulated that upcoming episodes would feature a love interest for Kurt.<ref name=\"Out\"/> Initial fan and media speculation suggested that [[Sam Evans]] ([[Chord Overstreet]]) was created to fill this role; however, according to Overstreet, Sam's storyline quickly paired him with [[Quinn Fabray]] ([[Dianna Agron]]) as a result of the chemistry the producers detected between him and Agron.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radaronline.com/exclusives/2010/10/audio-glees-chord-overstreet-says-sam-went-gay-straight|title=Audio: Glee's Chord Overstreet Says 'Sam' Went From Gay To Straight|date=October 13, 2010|work=[[RadarOnline]]|accessdate=October 13, 2010}}</ref> In September 2010, it was confirmed that Criss would join the show in a \"much-talked-about new gay role\".<ref name=\"darren criss cast\">{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/09/26/darren-criss-glee-kurt-boyfriend/|title=Scoop:Darren Criss joins 'Glee' as...Kurt's new BF?|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=September 26, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=March 6, 2011}}</ref> Media speculation suggested that Blaine would be Kurt's new love interest.<ref name=\"Out\">{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/slideshows/?slideshow_title=Darren-Criss-The-New-Kid-on-the-Block&theID=1#Top|title=The New Kid on the Block|last=Karpel|first=Ari|work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|publisher=[[Regent Media]]|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> His original character description was: \"a cute and charismatic gay student from a rival Glee club named the Dalton Academy Warblers\u2014will maintain a strictly platonic friendship with McKinley High's most out and proud pupil. But could that change as the season progresses? Yes, it could.\"<ref name=\"darren criss cast\"/> Murphy stated that Blaine's arc would be a significant one. He explained, \"He sort of becomes Kurt's mentor and then maybe love [...] Kurt really admires him and respects him.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.tvsquad.com/2010/09/30/news-roundup-ryan-murphy-confirms-chord-overstreet-will-not-pla/|title= News Roundup: Ryan Murphy Confirms Chord Overstreet Will Not Play Kurt's Boyfriend...|author= Bentley, Jean|work= [[AOL]] TV News|date= September 30, 2010|accessdate= October 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his first few appearances, it was reported that Criss had been confirmed as a series regular for the remainder of season two and for [[Glee (season 3)|season three]] of ''Glee''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/950912/glee-signs-darren-criss-as-series-regular|title=''Glee'' Signs Darren Criss As Series Regular|author=Ann Donahue|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company]]|accessdate=November 15, 2010}}</ref> This was based on comments by Murphy, who said: \"Darren has become such a sensation in one week, which I love. I think there's a hunger for him and a positive relationship role model. He\u2019ll definitely continue through the year and longer.\"<ref name=\"AE\"/> However, the actor later denied that his role had been upgraded and said: \"It's never really been officially confirmed to me. I think the option is there and that they want to keep Blaine around.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1652489/glee-guest-star-darren-criss-not-yet-series-regular.jhtml|title={{-'}}Glee' Guest Star Darren Criss Not Yet A Series Regular|author=Amy Wilkinson|publisher=MTV. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref> Murphy revealed that Blaine may join New Directions during the third season.<ref name=\"prom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/03/glee-scoop-kurt-and-blaine-prom-bound/#more-200615|title=Glee Scoop: Kurt and Blaine Are Prom-Bound!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|author2=Masters, Megan|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Criss hoped that this would not come to pass, as he enjoys being at Dalton Academy, but conceded: \"it's not my call. I'm happy to serve whatever story they want.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/04/ask-ausiello-spoilers-castle-how-i-met-your-mother-big-bang/#more-207140|title=Ask Ausiello: Spoilers on Castle, How I Met Your Mother, Psych, Gossip Girl, Big Bang, and More!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=April 12, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> For the [[Glee (season 3)|third season]] of ''Glee'', Criss was promoted to a series regular,<ref name=CrissShumJr.Regulars>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/07/glee-scoop-chord-overstreet-leaving/|title=Glee Exclusive: Darren Criss and Harry Shum Jr. In, Chord Overstreet Out!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=July 1, 2011|work=[[TV Line]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=July 1, 2011}}</ref> and Blaine did join New Directions when he transferred to McKinley High to be with Kurt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/09/glee-recap-back-to-school-and-basics-in-the-season-3-premiere.html|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: Back to school (and basics) in the Season 3 premiere|first=Amy|last=Reiter|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=September 21, 2011|accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Characterization===\n{{quote box\n|width = 32em\n|border = 1px\n|bgcolor=#c6dbf7\n|fontsize = 85%\n|quote = \"This is the first time I'd really seen an out student that was so young and innocent and really struggling with the big ordeal that it is to be an out student at such an early age. When other shows present the gay character thing, it's typically been in much more adult situations, like gay men living in New York or closeted men who are married and struggling with that ordeal, or having sex on the subway, but never really the core of the journey of defining your sexuality. Blaine offers a beautiful counter to that and makes such a great addition to the many-colored palette that is ''Glee''.\"\n|align = right\n|source = Criss on Blaine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/culture/darren-criss/|title=Darren Criss|last=Mendelson|first=Katie|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|publisher=[[Brant Publications]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref>}}\n\nUpon Blaine's first appearance, Criss described his character as being a \"very charismatic, put-together, composed guy.\" He stated that although Blaine is gay, he is not \"overly [[Effeminacy|queeny]], and not too [[Butch and femme|butch]] either,\" and that while his sexuality is a \"huge part of who he is\", it is not a major facet of how he wishes to be perceived. Due to similarities which stem from their shared sexuality, Blaine \"sees a lot of himself in Kurt, in terms of experiences and the way they feel about the world around them. He feels the need to impart his knowledge, be a source of strength for him, and really help him through what he's going through.\"<ref name=\"kurt's new squeeze\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/online/oscars/2010/11/darren-criss-battled-a-bear-to-get-on-glee-and-now-he-and-the-bear-are-very-good-friends.html|title=Glee\u2019s Darren Criss\u2014Kurt\u2019s New Squeeze?\u2014Describes His Character as \"Tom Ford-ish.\" Perfect!|last=Berk|first=Brett|date=November 9, 2010|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> Initially, Criss felt that the most important element of his character was to give Kurt \"someone he can relate to\", and demonstrate that Kurt could have \"a young out male friend, a support system\".<ref name=\"Out\"/>\n\nCriss discussed his personal connection with Blaine in an interview with ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''. He explained that he grew up among the \"gay community\", being with theater performers, so was raised without a concept of sexuality being an issue. Criss stated that, although he identifies as straight, \"it really doesn't come into play with me in this role. As an actor, your objective is always to play the scene. And this in case, he happens to be a gay teen.\"<ref name=\"kurt's new squeeze\"/> Talk show host and media personality [[Ellen DeGeneres]] deemed Blaine \"a very confident gay teen, which is something you don't see much on television.\"<ref name=\"Ellen Youtube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=649k4tPv8bI|title=Darren Criss sings for Ellen!|date=February 2, 2011|work=The Ellen DeGeneres Show|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> However, Amy Reiter of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' assessed that \"despite the image he projects, he, too, is just a kid trying to figure things out as he goes along.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/02/glee-recap-a-perfect-valentines-day-confection.html|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: A perfect Valentine's Day confection|last=Maerz|first=Melissa|date=February 8, 2011|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> Criss feels that Blaine's confidence is an important aspect of his character, as it is rare for gay teenagers on television to be so \"sure of themselves.\" He hopes that \"all the kids struggling with this issue can look to a guy like Blaine and feel [inspired] by his confidence.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/10/15/glee-darren-criss/|title={{-'}}Glee' Exclusive: Kurt's new (boy)friend speaks!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=October 15, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Relationships===\nThe Kurt\u2013Blaine relationship, sometimes referred to by the [[portmanteau]] \"Klaine\" by ''Glee'' fans and the media,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/02/glee-preview-silly-love-songs/#more-189636|title=Glee Valentine's Episode Preview: Your Burning Questions Answered!|last=Mitovich|first=Matt Webb|date=February 6, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> developed slowly. As the series showrunner, Murphy felt tasked with keeping the two apart as long as possible.<ref name=\"Out\"/> He was initially unsure whether the relationship would become a romantic one, and intended to gauge public response to their friendship before planning future developments. He commented, \"Part of me thinks he should be the boyfriend, part of me thinks he should just be the mentor. I didn't want to decide that until we got into sort of the middle of the season.\"<ref name=\"AE\"/> In December 2010, Colfer said, \"Fans really want it to happen. It's funny how many people want to see these boys hook up. We'll see.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2010/12/glees-chris-colfer-talks-golden-globes-tonsillitis-outbreaks-and-romance-with-blaine/#more-181384|title=Glee's Chris Colfer Talks Golden Globes, Tonsillitis Outbreaks, and Romance with Blaine|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=December 14, 2010|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> Based on the characters' chemistry and the \"immediate outcry\" from fans who wanted to see them as a couple, Murphy decided to have Blaine become Kurt's love interest. Criss noted: \"We all want to see Kurt happy, and like all great love stories, if you have two people that can be together you've got to hold it up.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20460138,00.html#20901379|title=Gay Teens on TV: A Timeline|last=D'Arminio|first=Aubry|date=March 2, 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nConsidering Blaine and Kurt's potential future together, Murphy planned to treat them the same as all other ''Glee'' relationships, by making their pairing \"as flawed and as exposed as everyone else's.\"<ref name=\"Out\"/> This sentiment was re-iterated by executive producer [[Brad Falchuk]], after the characters kissed for the first time. He revealed that their relationship would not run smoothly, and observed that once couples start dating, \"Everything goes to hell.\"<ref name=\"prom\"/> Colfer suggested that Kurt returning to McKinley may cause difficulties in their relationship, but noted \"Distance makes the heart grow fonder, right? That\u2019s what they tell me. So even if they do go through some bumps in the road, it would be very realistic.\"<ref name=\"prom\"/> In a Q&A with [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] on the day \"Born This Way\" ran with Kurt's McKinley return, Criss stated that Blaine and Kurt were \"in the honeymoon stages\" of their relationship, and would still be \"at the end of the [second] season\".<ref name=\"BillboardQA\">{{cite web|title=The Billboard Live Q&A: Darren Criss of \"Glee\", part 3 of 5 (at 6:39)|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/471891/glees-darren-criss-live-qa-video-archive|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 28, 2011|date=April 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a July 2012 interview with ''[[E! News]]'', Colfer said, \"I would like to do something besides say 'I love you,' and I think Darren [Criss] and I agree on that. We're ready for the next step. They've been together for a while. Let's throw some spice and drama into that.\" Colfer quipped that he did not know what was in store for the couple, \"I hear mixed things. I hear they're still together but then maybe they're breaking up.\"<ref name=\"enews\">{{cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/332350/glee-s-chris-colfer-wants-drama-for-kurt-blaine-hopes-to-sing-britney-spears-in-tribute-episode|title=Glee's Chris Colfer Wants \"Drama\" for Kurt & Blaine, Hopes to Sing Britney Spears in Tribute Episode|last=Maldon|first=Mark|date=July 23, 2012|work=[[E! News]]|publisher=[[NBC Universal]]|accessdate= December 26, 2012}}</ref> In September 2012, Criss seconded Colfer, \"We're like an old married couple now. Let's shake it up!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/332350/glee-s-chris-colfer-wants-drama-for-kurt-blaine-hopes-to-sing-britney-spears-in-tribute-episode|title=Glee's Darren Criss Wants Drama for Blaine and Kurt: \"Let's Shake It Up!\"|last=Maldon|first=Mark|date=September 7, 2012|work=E! News|publisher=NBC Universal|accessdate= December 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the second season episode \"Sexy\", Blaine reveals he has a strained relationship with his father.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Sexy|episodelink=Sexy (Glee)|series=Glee |series-link=Glee (TV series) |credits=[[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]] (director), [[Brad Falchuk]] (writer) |network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |airdate=March 8, 2011 |season=2 |number=15}}</ref>\n\n==Musical performances==\n[[File:Lea Michele by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Blaine's duet with Rachel (Michele, ''pictured'') marks his only appearance on ''Glee: The Music, Volume 5''.]]\n{{further|Glee discography|List of songs in Glee (season 2)|List of songs in Glee (season 3)|List of songs in Glee (season 4)}}\nAs Blaine, Criss features in many musical performances, which have been released as [[Single (music)|singles]], available for [[Music download|download]]. His first performance, \"[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry song)|Teenage Dream]]\" by [[Katy Perry]], was featured on the soundtrack album ''[[Glee: The Music, Volume 4]]''.<ref name=\"vol4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvsquad.com/2010/11/03/glee-the-music-volume-4-track-listing-released/|title={{-'}}Glee: The Music, Volume 4' Track Listing Released|date=November 3, 2010|first=Jean|last=Bentley|work=TV Squad|publisher=[[AOL]]|accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref> It reached number eight on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in the week ending November 27, 2010,<ref name=\"bill20101127\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-11-27/hot-100?order=gainer|title=Hot 100: Week of November 27, 2010 (Biggest Jump)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> and was the best-selling song in the U.S. that week, selling 214,000 copies: the largest figure for a ''Glee'' title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/e3i156046bdea3250ce85794b3b5746aded|title=A 'Dream' Come True: 'Glee' Cast and Susan Boyle Top Charts|date=November 17, 2010|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> It was only the second U.S.-certified gold single in the show's history.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Glee&format=&go=Search&perPage=50 |title=RIAA Gold & Platinum |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |accessdate=July 15, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130225031458/http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS |archivedate=February 25, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> Both ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'s}} Jillian Mapes and Erica Futterman of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' deemed \"Teenage Dream\" the best song of \"Never Been Kissed\", the episode in which it featured.<ref name=\"JM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/viral-videos/951288/glee-cast-shines-with-katy-perrys-teenage-dream|title={{-'}}Glee' Cast Shines With Katy Perry's 'Teenage Dream{{'-}}|date=November 10, 2010|first=Jillian|last=Mapes|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=November 10, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"EF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/glee-playback-chris-colfer-outshines-the-music-in-never-been-kissed-20101110|title={{-'}}Glee' Playback: Chris Colfer Outshines the Music in 'Never Been Kissed{{'-}}|date=November 10, 2010|first=Erica|last=Futterman|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=November 10, 2010|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/657jB1Y41?url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/glee-playback-chris-colfer-outshines-the-music-in-never-been-kissed-20101110|archive-date=February 1, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]''{{'s}} Anthony Benigno gave the song an \"A\", and noted that it was \"flawless\" and improved on Perry's original.<ref name=\"AB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2010/11/10/2010-11-10_glee_recap_never_been_kissed_introduces_darren_criss_and_gives_dot_jones_her_fir.html|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: 'Never Been Kissed' introduces Darren Criss and gives Dot Jones her first kiss|date=November 10, 2010|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|accessdate=November 10, 2010|location=New York City}}</ref> The performance was nominated for the Best Gay Moment of the Year and Favorite Music Video awards at the 2010 ''[[AfterEllen.com and AfterElton.com|AfterElton.com]]'' Visibility Awards.<ref name=\"AEV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afterelton.com/poll/2010/visibility-awards-winners |title=The AfterElton.com 2010 Visibility Awards&nbsp;\u2013 Winners |last=AfterElton.com Staff |date=December 20, 2010 |work=[[AfterEllen.com and AfterElton.com|AfterElton.com]] |publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]] |accessdate=January 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101065917/http://www.afterelton.com//poll//2010//visibility-awards-winners |archivedate=January 1, 2011 |df= }}</ref> A ''Billboard'' cover-feature on Criss noted that the performance \"arguably ushered in the trend of more current pop hits being reworked by the [''Glee''] cast.\"<ref name=\"MH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/472045/glees-darren-criss-the-billboard-cover-story|title={{-'}}Glee's' Darren Criss: The Billboard Cover Story|last=Herrera|first=Monica|date=April 15, 2011|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nLater songs performed by Blaine and the Warblers became popular enough to warrant a Warbler soundtrack album, ''Glee: The Music Presents the Warblers''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2011/03/08/glees-dalton-warblers-to-release-their-very-own-album/|title=''Glee''{{'s}} Dalton Warblers to Release Their Very Own Album|date=March 8, 2011|first=Elizabeth|last=Tyler|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=[[Time Inc]]|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> The tracks had sold over 1.3&nbsp;million copies as singles by the time the album was released.<ref name=\"holly\">{{Cite web|url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/03/23/glee-warblers-album/|title={{-'}}Glee' News: Warblers Album Tracklisting And Artwork Revealed!|date=March 23, 2011|first=James|last=Dinh|publisher=MTV. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> Blaine performed the lead vocal on covers of [[Train (band)|Train]]'s \"[[Hey, Soul Sister]]\", which peaked at number 32 in Canada,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aolradioblog.com/2010/11/24/glee-special-education-songs-season-2-episode-9/|title={{-'}}Glee' 'Special Education' Songs \u2013 Season 2, Episode 9|date=November 24, 2010|first=Nadina|last=Cheung|publisher=[[AOL Radio]] Blog. [[AOL]]|accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-12-18/canadian-hot-100?order=gainer|title=Canadian Hot 100: Week of December 18, 2010 (Biggest Jump)|date=December 18, 2010|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=December 9, 2010}}</ref> \"[[Bills, Bills, Bills]]\" by [[Destiny's Child]], which reached number 44 in the U.S.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/it_their_way_till_payday_JtT7UKzeKdC22secYRVJYN|title=It's their way, till payday|last=Wieselman|first=Jarett|date=February 3, 2011|work=[[New York Post]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=February 7, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204185715/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/it_their_way_till_payday_JtT7UKzeKdC22secYRVJYN|archive-date=February 4, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Vday\"/> and [[Robin Thicke]]'s \"[[When I Get You Alone]]\", which got to number 47 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"Vday\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/473015/lady-gaga-glee-highlight-historic-hot-100-week|title=Lady Gaga, 'Glee' Highlight Historic Hot 100 Week|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=February 16, 2011|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/12/glee-kurt-and-blaine-sing-when-i-get-you-alone-for-valentines-episode.html |title={{-'}}Glee': Kurt and Blaine sing 'When I Get You Alone' for Valentine's episode |date=December 27, 2010 |first=Hanh |last=Nguyen |publisher=[[Zap2it]]. [[Tribune Media Services]] |accessdate=January 17, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110129075625/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/12/glee-kurt-and-blaine-sing-when-i-get-you-alone-for-valentines-episode.html |archivedate=January 29, 2011 |df= }}</ref> Criss downplayed his performance of \"Bills, Bills, Bills\", and jested that he ought to issue the group's lead singer, [[Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]], an apology for his cover.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/darren-criss-secret-to-meeting-gwyneth-paltrow-on-glee-set-dental-floss_article_46808|title=Darren Criss\u2019 Secret To Meeting Gwyneth Paltrow On 'Glee' Set: Dental Floss|date=April 19, 2011|work=[[Access Hollywood]]|publisher=[[NBC]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Blaine also led on \"[[Silly Love Songs]]\" by [[Wings (band)|Wings]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/01/glee-scoop-from-globes-anne-hathaway-paul-mccartney-a-diva-off-and-more/|title=''Glee'' Scoop From Globes: Anne Hathaway, Paul McCartney, a Diva-Off and More!|date=January 17, 2011|first=Matt Webb|last=Mitovitch|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=January 17, 2011}}</ref> and [[Maroon 5]]'s \"[[Misery (Maroon 5 song)|Misery]]\",<ref name=\"zap16\">{{Cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/03/glee-hear-all-of-the-original-songs-and-covers-from-original-song.html |title={{-'}}Glee': Hear all of the original songs (and covers) from 'Original Song{{'-}} |date=March 11, 2011 |first=Mikey |last=O'Connell |publisher=[[Zap2it]]. [[Tribune Media Services]] |accessdate=March 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110314000303/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/03/glee-hear-all-of-the-original-songs-and-covers-from-original-song.html |archivedate=March 14, 2011 |df= }}</ref> which reached 45 and 52 respectively in the U.S.,<ref name=\"Vday\"/><ref name=\"CB\">{{Cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74345/week-ending-march-20-2011-songs-the-chris-brown-matter/ |title=Week Ending March 20, 2011: Songs: The Chris Brown Matter |date=March 23, 2011 |first=Paul |last=Grein |work=Chart Watch |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]] |accessdate=March 23, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430234208/http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74345/week-ending-march-20-2011-songs-the-chris-brown-matter/ |archivedate=April 30, 2011 |df= }}</ref> and [[Pink (singer)|Pink]]'s \"[[Raise Your Glass]]\", which peaked at number 30 in Australia.<ref name=\"zap16\"/><ref name=\"Aus\">{{Cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Glee+Cast|title=Discography Glee Cast|publisher=australian-charts.com. Hung Medien|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBlaine duetted with Kurt on [[Frank Loesser]]'s \"[[Baby, It's Cold Outside]]\", which was included on ''[[Glee: The Music, The Christmas Album]]'' and reached number 53 in Canada.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/glee-the-music-the-christmas-album--available-november-16-105757288.html|title=Glee: The Music, The Christmas Album \u2212 Available November 16|date=October 26, 2010|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|accessdate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-12-25/canadian-hot-100?order=gainer|title=Canadian Hot 100: Week of December 25, 2010 (Biggest Jump)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=December 16, 2010}}</ref> It was reportedly the most downloaded track of the album, and called \"by far the gayest thing that has ever been on TV\" by Colfer. Murphy expressed his pride in the number for \"push[ing] the envelope a bit.\"<ref name=\"BICO\"/> Jessica Ronayne of ''[[Zap2it]]'' called the duet one of the Christmas episode's few saving graces.<ref name=\"JessicaRonayne\">{{cite web|url=http://tvovermind.zap2it.com/tv-news/glee-season-2-episode-10-glee-christmas-review/40878|title=Glee Season 2 Episode 10 \"A Very Glee Christmas|first=Jessica|last=Ronayne|date=February 8, 2011|work=Zap2it|accessdate=April 15, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211221244/http://tvovermind.zap2it.com/tv-news/glee-season-2-episode-10-glee-christmas-review/40878|archivedate=February 11, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Blaine and Kurt also duetted on [[Neon Trees]]' \"[[Animal (Neon Trees song)|Animal]]\" and [[Hey Monday]]'s \"[[Candles (song)|Candles]]\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/03/glee-listen-to-kurt-and-blaine-perform-neon-trees-animal.html |title={{-'}}Glee': Listen to Kurt and Blaine perform Neon Trees' 'Animal{{'-}} |date=March 4, 2011 |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |publisher=[[Zap2it]]. [[Tribune Media Services]] |accessdate=March 23, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307092349/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/03/glee-listen-to-kurt-and-blaine-perform-neon-trees-animal.html |archivedate=March 7, 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/472501/glees-new-directions-blaine-and-kurt-score-big-at-regionals|title={{-'}}Glee's' New Directions, Blaine and Kurt Score Big at Regionals|date=March 16, 2011|first=Katie|last=Morgan|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|location=New York|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> which peaked at 62 and 71 in the U.S. respectively.<ref name=\"CB\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74342/week-ending-march-13-2011-spears-second-act/ |title=Week Ending March 13, 2011: Spears' Second Act |date=March 16, 2011 |first=Paul |last=Grein |work=Chart Watch |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]] |accessdate=March 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321023907/http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74342/week-ending-march-13-2011-spears-second-act |archivedate=March 21, 2011 }}</ref> In an April 2011 interview, Criss stated that he did not feel established enough within the cast to make song suggestions, but had mentioned liking \"Animal\" to Murphy, who included it in a script soon thereafter.<ref name=\"MH\"/> Blaine shared a duet of \"[[Don't You Want Me]]\" by [[The Human League]] with Rachel, which Reiter deemed a musical highlight of the episode \"[[Blame It on the Alcohol]]\".<ref name= \"amyreiter2\" /> It was included on ''[[Glee: The Music, Volume 5]]'', and peaked at number 44 in Australia.<ref name=\"Aus\"/><ref>{{Cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/glee-debuts-original-songs-on-glee-the-music-volume-5-available-march-8-116643439.html|title=Glee Debuts Original Songs on Glee: The Music, Volume 5 Available March 8|date=February 22, 2011|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|accessdate=February 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of the season, Blaine's musical performances leading the Warblers became so prevalent that he was called out for it on-screen. Criss offered the insight: \"Blaine definitely had his moment in the sun. I think it's time to focus back on the characters that fans of the show really know and love. Completely objectively from watching the show, I was like, 'Why does Blaine get all these songs? This is ridiculous. I want to hear other people doing stuff.' I think we're focusing a little more back on New Directions and taking a little bit of a break from the Warblers.\"<ref name=\"MH\"/>\n\nIn the first episode of [[Glee (season 3)|season three]] of ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', \"[[The Purple Piano Project]]\", Blaine sings \"[[It's Not Unusual]]\" by [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]] when he transfers to McKinley and quits the Warblers for New Directions. After successfully auditioning later in the season for the school's production of ''[[West Side Story]]'' with \"Something's Coming\" from the musical, he sings \"[[Tonight (1956 song)|Tonight]]\" in rehearsal and \"One Hand, One Heart\" in performance, both with his co-star Rachel. He sings lead or co-lead on several songs with New Directions, including \"[[Last Friday Night (T.G.I.F.)]]\"; \"[[Fuckin' Perfect|Perfect]]\" and \"[[Let It Snow! Let It Snow! Let It Snow!]]\" with Kurt; \"[[Control (Janet Jackson song)|Control]]\" and \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\" with Artie and others; and his first original song, the duet \"Extraordinary Merry Christmas\", with Rachel.\n\nIn special tribute episode to [[Michael Jackson]], \"[[Michael (Glee)|Michael]]\", Blaine sings \"[[Wanna Be Startin' Somethin']]\". Futterman wrote that Blaine's \"slick showmanship\" made him a \"natural for lead vocals\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/glee-recap-a-tribute-worthy-of-a-king-20120201 |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: A Tribute Worthy of a King |last=Futterman |first=Erica |date=February 1, 2012 |work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> and ''[[TVLine]]''{{'}}s Michael Slezak called it \"the best use of Darren Criss' voice on Glee in quite some time\" and gave it an \"A\u2212\". ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'s}} Joseph Brannigan Lynch also gave it an \"A\u2212\", and said Criss \"captured the excitement and the spunky bravado of the original\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/glee-michael-jackson-episode/|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: An 'Off the Wall' Tribute to MJ |last=Lynch|first=Joseph Brannigan|date=February 1, 2012|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> [[MTV]]'s Kevin P. Sullivan was another fan of \"the sheer awesomeness of Darren Criss\" on the song, and characterized it as \"a tribute that's more respectful than any other in the episode\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2012/02/01/glee-recap-michael/ |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: 'Michael{{'-}}|date=February 1, 2012|first=Kevin P. |last=Sullivan|work=Hollywood Crush|publisher=[[MTV Networks]]|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref>\nIn the fourteenth episode of the third season, \"[[On My Way (Glee)|On My Way]]\", Blaine performs \"[[Cough Syrup (song)|Cough Syrup]]\" by [[Young the Giant]], which is sung during the [[Dave Karofsky]] suicide sequence. Futterman said Blaine \"flawlessly deliver[ed] the vocal\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/glee-recap-whats-going-on-20120222 |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: What's Going On? |last=Futterman |first=Erica |work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |date=February 22, 2012 |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> Lynch called it a \"chilling rendition\" that was \"hard to shake\" and gave it an {{nowrap|\"A\u2212\",}} the same grade given by Slezak, who wrote, \"taken on its own, Blaine's vocal was strong and passionate\u2014perhaps better than the original\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2012/02/glee-recap-season-3-episode-14-on-my-way-who-won-regionals/|title=''Glee'' Recap: A Very Special Cliffhanger |first=Michael|last=Slezak|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|date=February 21, 2012|accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/glee-season-3-winter-finale-quinn-cliffhanger/|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: To Be Continued... What?! |last=Lynch|first=Joseph Brannigan|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=February 22, 2012|accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> Bobby Hankinson of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' said it was the \"best\" of the episode, and added that the \"scene was really, really well done and carried maximum emotional punch\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.chron.com/tubular/2012/02/glee-gets-serious-real-serious/|title=''Glee'' gets serious. Real serious. |first=Bobby|last=Hankinson|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|publisher=Jack Sweeney|date=February 22, 2012|accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> In the following episode, \"[[Big Brother (Glee)|Big Brother]]\", Blaine shares a duet of [[Gotye]]'s \"[[Somebody That I Used to Know]]\" with his brother Cooper ([[Matt Bomer]]). Crystal Bell of ''[[HuffPost TV]]'' called it the \"highlight of the episode\", and it was Hankinson's favorite performance: \"Bomer and Criss did a fantastic job bringing it to life\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.chron.com/tubular/2012/04/glee-a-master-class-in-handsome-with-blaine-and-cooper/|title=''Glee'': A master class in handsome with Blaine and Cooper |first=Bobby|last=Hankinson|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|publisher=Jack Sweeney|date=April 10, 2012|accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/crystal-bell/glee-recap-big-brother_b_1416019.html |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: Matt Bomer Brings Brotherly Love To McKinley |first=Crystal|last=Bell|work=HuffPost TV|date=April 10, 2012|accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> Futterman said that \"it was initially disconcerting to envision\" two brothers singing about a \"former love\", but she noted that it \"was less weird in context\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/glee-recap-somebody-that-i-used-to-know-20120411 |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: Somebody That I Used to Know |last=Futterman |first=Erica |work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |date=April 11, 2012 |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> In its first week, the cover sold 152,000 digital downloads in the US, and was number twenty-six on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"US\">Peak chart positions for season 3 singles in the United States: \"Somebody That I Used to Know\" and \"Hungry Like the Wolf / Rio\": {{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2012-04-28/hot-100?order=gainer|title=Hot 100: Week of April 28, 2012 (Biggest Jump)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=May 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nBlaine has received mostly positive reviews from television critics. Ellen DeGeneres praised Criss's portrayal, and described him as one of ''Glee''{{'s}} breakout stars.<ref name=\"Ellen Youtube\" /> ''Entertainment Weekly'' named him one of the breakout stars of 2010, with the comment: \"It took about 2 minutes and 11 seconds on ''Glee'' for Darren Criss to turn into a bona fide Gleek phenomenon. [...] And it doesn't hurt that his character Blaine's warm relationship with the show's other openly gay character, Chris Colfer's Kurt, continues to resonate with fans.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20430932_20452138,00.html#20890408|title=16 Breakout Stars of 2010|date=December 20, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> In November 2010, the publication also named Criss the series' best guest-star to date, and praised him for \"seamlessly entering the fold with his charm and great voice.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20302134_20442853,00.html#20877290|title={{-'}}Glee': Ranking the Best Guest Stars|last=Exton|first=Emily|date=November 18, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Ronayne deemed him \"a much better addition to the show than [[Chord Overstreet]]\".<ref name=\"JessicaRonayne\"/> Following his ''Glee'' debut, Criss won the We're Wilde About You Rising Star Award at the 2011 Dorian Awards, presented by the Gay and Lesbian Entertainment Critics Association.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/glee-i-love-score-dorian-72969|title={{-'}}Glee,' 'I Am Love' Score Dorian Awards|last=Kilday|first=Gregg|date=January 18, 2011|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=January 25, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118014169.html?categoryId=13&cs=1|title=Voting deadline for Academy members closing in|last=''Variety'' staff|date=January 21, 2010|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> He also won the 2011 Teen Choice Award for Choice TV Breakout Star.<ref name=\"HolRep\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/teen-choice-awards-2011-winners-220172|title=Teen Choice Awards 2011 Winners Revealed |first=Kimberly |last=Nordyke |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 7, 2011 |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIndecision over his sexuality in the episode \"[[Blame It on the Alcohol]]\" drew some negative reviews of Blaine. Reiter noted that, \"So much of Blaine's charm has been his certainty about who he is.\" Though she found his subplot with Rachel \"fun\", she commented: \"Blaine's overwrought speech in the coffee shop after Rachel asks him out just felt off-key. Saying 'bye' to the Blaine sexual-confusion storyline wouldn't make us angry at all.\"<ref name= \"amyreiter2\">{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/02/glee-recap-making-alcohol-awareness-sing.html|title={{-'}}Glee' recap: Making alcohol awareness sing!|last=Reiter|first=Amy|date=February 22, 2011|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=February 23, 2011}}</ref> Emily VanDerWerff of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' also criticised the storyline, which, she wrote, \"seemed like it might be an interesting, complicated look at teenage [[Human sexuality|sexuality]] and how it can seem formed but might be more fluid than most teens would give it credit for, then lost its nerve and took the easy way out.\"<ref name=\"avclub\">{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/blame-it-on-the-alcohol,52122/ |title=Blame It on the Alcohol |last=VanDerWerff |first=Emily |date=February 22, 2011 |work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> ''AfterElton.com''{{'s}} Chris O'Guinn felt that the only aspect of the storyline handled acceptably was Blaine questioning whether he was bisexual, rather than outright straight. He criticized the shallow examination of his feelings, and wrote: \"Bisexuality is such a contentious issue that it should not be fumbled this way. For a character to say 'maybe I'm bi' in one scene and then the next say, 'nope, definitely gay' is almost cruel in how dismissive it is toward bisexuals by trivializing the intense confusion that many bisexual people feel in coming to terms with their orientation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterelton.com/oysters/03/16/11?page=0%2C1|title=Snails & Oysters: The Bisexual Perspective on ... \"Buffy\" and \"Glee\"|last=O'Guinn|first=Chris|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[AfterEllen.com and AfterElton.com|AfterElton.com]]|publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> In a more positive review, Canning opined that Blaine and Kurt's conversation about sexuality was \"great\". He was \"glad it wasn't an easy talk for either of them\" and said that it \"felt very real for kids in this situation.\"<ref name=\"IGN-BIOTA\">{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/115/1151578p1.html|title=Glee: \"Blame It On the Alcohol\" Review|last=Canning|first=Robert|date=February 23, 2011|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=April 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Chris Colfer 2011 Shankbone.JPG|thumb|right|150px|The relationship between Blaine and Kurt (Colfer, ''pictured'') has been generally well received by critics.]]\nBlaine and Kurt's relationship has been generally well received. They were named Favorite TV Couple at the 2010 ''AfterElton.com'' Visibility Awards,<ref name=\"AEV\"/> and have been lauded for \"leading the way\" in representing gay teenagers on television by ''Entertainment Weekly''.<ref name=\"BICO\">{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/01/20/glee-gay-teens-ew-cover/|title=This week's cover: How 'Glee' is leading TV's gay-teen revolution|date=January 20, 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Jarett Wieselman of the ''[[New York Post]]'' referred to them as \"one of the most beloved TV couples of the millennium\".<ref name=\"NYP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/chris_colfer_8cb1mvxH33ELSaIhQEza5O |title=It's Chris Colfer's Time |last=Wieselman |first=Jarett |date=April 21, 2011 |work=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=April 21, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424033957/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/chris_colfer_8cb1mvxH33ELSaIhQEza5O |archivedate=April 24, 2011 |df= }}</ref> When they \"finally solidified what their relationship actually is\" in the episode \"[[Silly Love Songs (Glee)|Silly Love Songs]]\", ''[[IGN]]''{{'s}} Robert Canning noted that his opinion of Blaine improved. He commented: \"I love that the [serenading of Jeremiah] blew up in Blaine's face. The character has always come off to me as annoyingly arrogant, but \"Silly Love Songs\" humanized the guy. Guess I may have to like him now.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/114/1148604p1.html|title=Glee: \"Silly Love Songs\" Review|last=Canning|first=Robert|date=February 8, 2011|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> Their first kiss, in the episode \"[[Original Song]]\", was met with critical acclaim. Mark Perigard of ''[[The Boston Herald]]'' wrote, \"It was utterly, sweetly romantic, and Criss sold the hell out of the moment. It's long overdue and it will silence the growing legion of critics out there who were unhappy with the pace of this story.\"<ref name=\"BostonH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/blogs/entertainment/love_that_tv/?p=484|title={{-'}}Glee': Klaine takes off, Rachel hits bottom|last=Perigard|first=Mark|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[Boston Herald]]|publisher=Herald Media Inc.|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} Mandi Bierly was so impressed with the scene that she was initially concerned it may be a dream sequence, \"because we don't get romantic, unapologetic first kisses like that between young gay characters on network TV.\" She wrote, \"Relationships aren't easy. They\u2019ll make mistakes. But if they stay true to themselves, and continue to be as open and honest with each other, we're in for something special.\"<ref name=\"MB\">{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/03/16/glee-kurt-blaine-kiss/|title={{-'}}Glee': Anyone else think that dreamy Blaine/Kurt moment had to be a dream?|last=Bierly|first=Mandi|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Kevin Fallon of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' thought the kiss was \"sweet\", and stated that he was pleased that it attracted no controversy whatsoever.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2011/03/on-glee-two-boys-kiss-without-controversy/72571/|title=On 'Glee,' Two Boys Kiss, Without Controversy|last=Fallon|first=Kevin|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> Aly Semigran of MTV praised the interaction between Blaine and Kurt. She called the kiss scene a \"sweet, real and, shockingly, un-hyped moment\", and praised Criss and Colfer for \"handl[ing] it with dignity and honesty\".<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/03/16/glee-recap-original-song/|title=Glee Recap Original Song|last=Semigran|first=Aly|date=March 16, 2011|publisher=MTV. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhile Lesley Goldberg of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' was pleased Blaine's season three transfer to McKinley in the first episode increased Criss' screen time with Colfer and the New Directions cast, she stated that the move \"screams of co-dependency.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/glee-season-3-premiere-hits-238003|title={{-'}}Glee' Season 3 Premiere: Hits and Misses|first=Lesley|last=Goldberg|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=September 20, 2011|accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref> In contrast, ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} Abby West found it romantic, and noted: \"Blaine and Kurt, with their budding love and witty, pseudo-urbane ways, are my favorite couple to watch. ... I look forward to hearing [Blaine] sing more, watching him bump up against the insular Glee clubbers, and seeing him show off his non-uniform attire\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/glee-season-3-episode-1-purple-piano-project/|title={{-'}}Glee' season premiere recap: Join the Club!|first=Abby|last=West|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|date=September 21, 2011|accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref> Several reviewers were unhappy with the second episode's revelation that Blaine was a junior, not a senior like Kurt, as had been implied in the previous season. VanDerWerff wrote that Blaine \"seems to have simultaneously gotten younger and had a complete personality transplant over the summer\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'s}} Rae Votta noted \"the continuity-bending plot point that he's somehow a Junior and not a Senior like his boyfriend\", and Samantha Urban of ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' allowed her exasperation to show: \"Oh really, ''Glee''? Blaine's a junior? Blaine's younger than Kurt? Fine. FINE.\"<ref name=\"AV302\">{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/i-am-unicorn,62295/|title={{-\"}}I Am Unicorn{{\"-}}|first=Emily|last=VanDerWerff|date=September 27, 2011|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"BBRV302\">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/467229/glee-has-mommy-issues-in-plot-aplenty-episode|title={{-'}}Glee' Has Mommy Issues in Plot-Aplenty Episode|first=Rae|last=Votta|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=September 28, 2011|accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Dallas302\">{{Cite web|url=http://popcultureblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2011/09/tv-recap-glee---i-am-unicorn.html |title=TV recap: \"Glee\" \u2013 'I Am Unicorn{{'-}} |date=September 28, 2011 |first=Samantha |last=Urban |work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |accessdate=September 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003210756/http://popcultureblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2011/09/tv-recap-glee---i-am-unicorn.html |archivedate=October 3, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\nKurt and Blaine make the decision to have sex for the first time in \"[[The First Time (Glee)|The First Time]]\" episode; many critics were enthusiastic about the fact that a gay couple was being given such a storyline. Canning said that Kurt and Blaine's \"attempts to get a little wild\", and \"trying to grow up faster than they should\", were \"the better parts of the episode as they felt the most realistic\".<ref name=\"IGN-TheFirstTime\">{{cite web |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/121/1212004p1.html |title=Glee: \"The First Time\" Review |last=Canning |first=Robert |date=November 9, 2011 |work=IGN |publisher=News Corporation|accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref> Futterman praised their departure from the bar as a \"very faithful and honest scene\".<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/glee-recap-the-first-time-tries-too-hard-20111109 |title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: 'The First Time' Tries Too Hard |last=Futterman |first=Erica |date=November 9, 2011 |work=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref> VanDerWerff and [[BuddyTV]] contributor John Kubicek both had issues with Blaine's characterization. The latter asserted that he \"just behaves however the writers need him to behave in order for the scene to work\", while the former said that Blaine's season three storyline \"hasn\u2019t been bad by any means, but it does feel like Darren Criss is playing someone who\u2019s quite a bit different from the guy he was playing last season\".<ref name=\"Buddy\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/glee/glee-recap-the-agony-of-sex-42559.aspx|title={{-'}}Glee' Recap: The Agony of Sex|date=November 8, 2011|first=John|last=Kubicek|publisher=BuddyTV|accessdate=November 23, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110112426/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/glee/glee-recap-the-agony-of-sex-42559.aspx|archive-date=November 10, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bell was impressed by the way the characters' relationship \"inspires gay youth in a way that we haven't seen on network television yet\" and called them \"amazing role models for all teens\", and ''The Atlantic'' writer Kevin Fallon said it was \"remarkable\" and a \"milestone\" that \"the decision by gay teen characters to lose their virginities is given equal weight to that of a straight couple\".<ref name=\"ATL\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/11/how-glee-got-teen-sex-right/248157/ |title=How 'Glee' Got Teen Sex Right |date=November 9, 2011 |last1=Fallon |first1=Kevin |work=The Atlantic |publisher=Atlantic Media Company|accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDiscussing public response to his character, Criss stated that he particularly enjoyed comments from \"people from parts of the world who are maybe not as exposed to certain ideologies\", but had reconsidered their stance on relationships and human rights as a result of the Blaine\u2013Kurt storyline. He called this response \"phenomenal\", and said: \"I was a straight kid growing up in a very gay community and it's something that I've had to watch so many friends have to struggle with and have no place to go to identify in kind of a grander media culture. To be a small piece of that machine is incredibly wonderful.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterelton.com/people/2011/01/darren-criss-glee-teenage-dream?page=0%2C1|title=Interview: Darren Criss Humbly Calls Himself \"Last Grain of Sand{{\"-}}|last=Jensen|first=Michael|date=January 18, 2011|work=[[AfterEllen.com and AfterElton.com|AfterElton.com]]|publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]|accessdate=April 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Glee}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Blaine}}\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2010]]\n[[Category:Fictional gay males]]\n[[Category:Fictional LGBT characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional singers]]\n[[Category:Glee (TV series) characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional pianists]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "name_user": "63.134.167.216", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blaine_Anderson"}
{"title_page": "National Soccer League US", "text_new": "[[File:Nsln01 (1)7001.png|thumb]]\n[http://www.nationalsoccerleague.us/ National Soccer League US]\nThe National Soccer League US is A United States National Soccer League in the US Soccer Open Division with Conferences in more than 20 States and 3 Divisions: NSL Premier, NSL First and NSL Academy for men's soccer and the NSL Women its Women's branch plus NSL Soccer Youth League, the Development branch for boys and girls teams, clubs and academies U8 to U17.\n\nThe National Soccer League US in the continuation of the leagues such as Miami Soccer League, Florida Soccer League, Texas Soccer League, New York City Soccer League, Georgia Soccer League, North Carolina Soccer League that originally competed from the year 2000 to the year 2012 under the network umbrella of the National Soccer Leagues US.\n\nThe National Soccer League US is sanctioned by USSSA member of the United States Soccer Federation, therefore teams, clubs and academies can participate in the official US Open Cup championship of the Unites States Soccer Federation in which MLS clubs participate, USL Championship , USL One, NISA, USL Two, NPSL and different teams from the US Soccer Open Division.\n\nAs a member of the National Champions League, teams from the National Soccer League US participate directly in the USSSA Soccer NCL National Tournament. The National Soccer League US Conferences are managed by the NSL State Director together with the Different Managers of the major cities of each conference that are NSL Florida, NSL Texas, NSL New York, NSL New Jersey, NSL Georgia, NSL North Carolina , NSL Michigan, NSL Indiana, NSL Tenesi, NSL South Carolina, NSL Kansas, NSL Mississippi, NSL Atlantic, NSL Philadelphia.\n\nThe US Soccer Open Division to which the National Soccer League US belongs, is the division of the US Soccer Federation where non-professional Clubs play and do not belong to the First Professional Division, MLS, the Second Professional Division, USL Championship and the Third Professional Division, USL One and NISA.\n", "text_old": "[[File:Nsln01 (1)7001.png|thumb]]\nThe National Soccer League US is A United States National Soccer League in the US Soccer Open Division with Conferences in more than 20 States and 3 Divisions: NSL Premier, NSL First and NSL Academy for men's soccer and the NSL Women its Women's branch plus NSL Soccer Youth League, the Development branch for boys and girls teams, clubs and academies U8 to U17.\n\nThe National Soccer League US in the continuation of the leagues such as Miami Soccer League, Florida Soccer League, Texas Soccer League, New York City Soccer League, Georgia Soccer League, North Carolina Soccer League that originally competed from the year 2000 to the year 2012 under the network umbrella of the National Soccer Leagues US.\n\nThe National Soccer League US is sanctioned by USSSA member of the United States Soccer Federation, therefore teams, clubs and academies can participate in the official US Open Cup championship of the Unites States Soccer Federation in which MLS clubs participate, USL Championship , USL One, NISA, USL Two, NPSL and different teams from the US Soccer Open Division.\n\nAs a member of the National Champions League, teams from the National Soccer League US participate directly in the USSSA Soccer NCL National Tournament. The National Soccer League US Conferences are managed by the NSL State Director together with the Different Managers of the major cities of each conference that are NSL Florida, NSL Texas, NSL New York, NSL New Jersey, NSL Georgia, NSL North Carolina , NSL Michigan, NSL Indiana, NSL Tenesi, NSL South Carolina, NSL Kansas, NSL Mississippi, NSL Atlantic, NSL Philadelphia.\n\nThe US Soccer Open Division to which the National Soccer League US belongs, is the division of the US Soccer Federation where non-professional Clubs play and do not belong to the First Professional Division, MLS, the Second Professional Division, USL Championship and the Third Professional Division, USL One and NISA.\n", "name_user": "Miamitango", "label": "safe", "comment": "Pagina Editada Link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Soccer_League_US"}
{"title_page": "Wally Westmore", "text_new": "[[File:DrJekyllandMrHyde1931D.png|thumb|Wally Westmore's make-up transformed [[Fredric March]]'s [[Doctor Jekyll]] into the grotesquely simian [[Mr Hyde]].]]'''Walter 'Wally' James Westmore''' (February 13, 1906 \u2013 July 3, 1973) was a [[make-up artist]] for [[Hollywood]] [[film]]s.\n\nWestmore was one of [[Westmore family|six brothers]]; all became notable film make-up artists.  They were [[Monte Westmore|Monte]], [[Perc Westmore|Perc]], [[Ern Westmore|Ern]], Wally, [[Bud Westmore|Bud]] and [[Frank Westmore|Frank]].\n\nWally Westmore's career began with the highly successful ''[[Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde (1931 film)|Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde]]'' (1931) in which the transition of [[Fredric March]] from Jekyll to Hyde was considered groundbreaking in the field of film make-up.    He eventually went on to work on more than 300 films, mostly for [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]].\n\n==Filmography==\nSome of his more notable films include:\n*''[[Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde (1931 film)|Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde]]'' (1931)\n*''[[Island of Lost Souls (1932 film)|Island of Lost Souls]]'' (1932)\n*''[[North West Mounted Police (film)|North West Mounted Police]]'' (1940)\n*''[[The Lady Eve]]'' (1941)\n*''[[Sullivan's Travels]]'' (1941)\n*''[[I Married a Witch]]'' (1942)\n*''[[Holiday Inn (film)|Holiday Inn]]'' (1942)\n*''[[Road to Morocco]]'' (1942)\n*''[[Five Graves to Cairo]]'' (1943)\n*''[[For Whom the Bell Tolls (film)|For Whom the Bell Tolls]]'' (1943)\n*''[[Going My Way]]'' (1944)\n*''[[Double Indemnity (film)|Double Indemnity]]'' (1944)\n*''[[Kitty (1945 film)|''Kitty'' (1945 film)]]'' (1945)\n*''[[The Strange Love of Martha Ivers]]'' (1946)\n*''[[Blue Skies (1946 film)|Blue Skies]]'' (1946)\n*''[[California (1947 film)|California]]'' (1947)\n*''[[My Favorite Brunette]]'' (1947)\n*''[[The Perils of Pauline (1947 film)|''The Perils of Pauline'' (1947 film)]]'' (1947)\n*''[[Desert Fury]]'' (1947)\n*''[[Unconquered (1947 film)|Unconquered]]'' (1947)\n*''[[Road to Rio]]'' (1947)\n*''[[The Big Clock (film)|The Big Clock]]'' (1948)\n*''[[The Emperor Waltz]]'' (1948)\n*''[[A Foreign Affair]]'' (1948)\n*''[[Sorry, Wrong Number]]'' (1948)\n*''[[Whispering Smith]]'' (1948)\n*''[[The Paleface (1948 film)|The Paleface]]'' (1948)\n*''[[A Connecticut Yankee in King Arthur's Court (1949 film)|A Connecticut Yankee in King Arthur's Court]]'' (1949)\n*''[[Streets of Laredo (film)|''Streets of Laredo'' (film)]]'' (1949)\n*''[[The Heiress]]'' (1949)\n*''[[Sorrowful Jones]]'' (1949)\n*''[[Samson and Delilah (1949 film)|Samson and Delilah]]'' (1949)\n*''[[The File on Thelma Jordon]]'' (1950)\n*''[[Sunset Boulevard (1950 film)|Sunset Boulevard]]'' (1950)\n*''[[Union Station (film)|''Union Station'' (film)]]'' (1950)\n*''[[A Place in the Sun (film)|A Place in the Sun]]'' (1951)\n*''[[Here Comes the Groom]]'' (1951)\n*''[[Red Mountain (film)|Red Mountain]]'' (1952)\n*''[[My Favorite Spy]]'' (1951)\n*''[[The Greatest Show on Earth (film)|The Greatest Show on Earth]]'' (1952)\n*''[[Denver and Rio Grande (film)|Denver and Rio Grande]]'' (1952)\n*''[[Carrie (1952 film)|''Carrie'' (1952 film)]]'' (1952)\n*''[[Son of Paleface]]'' (1952)\n*''[[Just for You (1952 film)|''Just for You'' (1952 film)]]'' (1952)\n*''[[Road to Bali]]'' (1952)\n*''[[Come Back, Little Sheba (1952 film)|Come Back, Little Sheba]]'' (1952)\n*''[[The War of the Worlds (1953 film)|The War of the Worlds]]'' (1953)\n*''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]'' (1953)\n*''[[Stalag 17]]'' (1953)\n*''[[Arrowhead (1953 film)|''Arrowhead'' (1953 film)]]'' (1953)\n*''[[The Caddy]]'' (1953)\n*''[[Roman Holiday (1953 film)|Roman Holiday]]'' (1953)\n*''[[Red Garters (film)|''Red Garters'' (film)]]'' (1954)\n*''[[The Naked Jungle]]'' (1954)\n*''[[Elephant Walk]]'' (1954)\n*''[[Rear Window]]'' (1954)\n*''[[Sabrina (1954 film)| Sabrina]]'' (1954)\n*''[[To Catch a Thief (film)|To Catch a Thief]]'' (1955)\n*''[[The Trouble with Harry]]'' (1955)\n*''[[The Rose Tattoo (film)|The Rose Tattoo]]'' (1955)\n*''[[The Man Who Knew Too Much (1956 film)|The Man Who Knew Too Much]]'' (1956)\n*''[[The Proud and Profane]]'' (1956)\n*''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' (1956)\n*''[[The Rainmaker (1956 film)|The Rainmaker]]'' (1956)\n*''[[Funny Face]]'' (1957)\n*''[[Gunfight at the O.K. Corral (film)|Gunfight at the O.K. Corral]]'' (1957)\n*''[[Loving You (1957 film)|Loving you]]'' (1957)\n*''[[The Tin Star]]'' (1957)\n*''[[Desire Under the Elms (film)|Desire Under the Elms]]'' (1958)\n*''[[Teacher's Pet (1958 film)|Teacher's Pet]]'' (1958)\n*''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958)\n*''[[King Creole]]'' (1958)\n*''[[The Space Children]]'' (1958)<ref>Warren, Bill (1986). \"Keep Watching The Skies Volume 2\". McFarland & Co., Inc. {{ISBN|0-89950-170-2}}. Page 766 </ref>\n*''[[The Five Pennies]]'' (1959)\n*''[[That Kind of Woman]]'' (1959)\n*''[[Career (1959 film)|Career]]'' (1959)\n*''[[Li'l Abner (1959 film)|Li'l Abner]]'' (1959)\n*''[[Visit to a Small Planet]]'' (1960)\n*''[[One-Eyed Jacks]]'' (1961)\n*''[[The Ladies' Man]]' (1961)\n*''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]'' (1961)\n*''[[Summer and Smoke (film)|Summer and Smoke]]'' (1961)\n*''[[The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance]]'' (1962)\n*''[[Hud (1963 film)|Hud]]'' (1963)\n*''[[Love with the Proper Stranger]]'' (1963)\n*''[[Barefoot in the Park (film)|Barefoot in the Park]]'' (1967)\n*''[[The Odd Couple (film)|The Odd Couple]]'' (1968)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Westmore family]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0922885}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westmore, Wally}}\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:British make-up artists]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)]]\n\n\n{{US-film-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Walter 'Wally' James Westmore''' (February 13, 1906 \u2013 July 3, 1973) was a [[make-up artist]] for [[Hollywood]] [[film]]s.\n\nWestmore was one